      <title>Oscar Pistorius trial: pathologist gives different sequence of bullets</title>
      <description><![CDATA[Pathologist Jan Botha, the first defence witness, presented a different sequence of bullets to the court from the prosecution’s on day 17 of Oscar Pistorius’s murder trial. Botha told the court that Reeva Steenkamp would not have screamed, as Oscar Pistorius could have fired four shots within four seconds. She would have been in a state of pain, shock and fear. Botha believed that Steenkamp had been standing close to the toilet door. The first bullet hit her right hip, making her lose her balance.The second shot hit her in the right arm.The third shot injured Steenkamp’s left hand and then ricocheted off the wall.The prosecution established that Steenkamp had eaten at 1:00 a.m., two hours before her death. But Botha argued that ‘gastric emptying’ was not a scientific way to determine time of death.Botha said the bladder fills at a rate of 60ml an hour. If Steenkamp's bladder was empty, it meant that she had urinated before the shooting.Pistorius began vomiting as Botha was describing grisly details on Steenkamp’s wounds.]]></description>
