      <title>34th America's Cup: A guide to the AC72 boat</title>
      <description><![CDATA[The 34th America's Cup gets underway in San Francisco on Sunday when Team New Zealand, Luna Rossa and Artemis will battle for the Louis Vuitton Cup challenger series, with the winner going on to contest the America's Cup with reigning champion Oracle.This year's event will use the revolutionary AC72-class catarmarans, which have a crew of 11 and stand 40 meters tall.These 22m long, high tech twin-hulled boats are constructed of composite materials and feature rigid sails and foils to maximise speeds.The rigids sails work like aircraft wings, creating unequal pressure zones that can see the vessels achieve speeds more than twice the windspeed.While the foils enable the boat to lift out of the water at high speed, eliminating drag and pushing the top speeds up to  around 40 knots, or 74 kilometers per hour.But with added speed comes risk. The boats have been known to pitchpole, when the stern pitches forward over the bow.An incident in May when the Artemis boat pitchpoled resulted in the death of British Olympic gold medallist Andrew Simpson.]]></description>
