      <title>Curiosity Mars rover to look for signs of life</title>
      <description><![CDATA[The Mars Science Laboratory was launched from Cape Canaveral on Nov. 26, 2011 and is scheduled to land the Mars Curiosity rover on August 5. The chief goal of the $2.5 billion mission is to look for signs of life.The Curiosity Mars rover can drill to a depth of two inches. At two inches, complex organic molecules, better signs of past life than simple organic molecules, are destroyed by cosmic rays after a few hundred million years.If the rover finds complex organic molecules, it will likely do so in a crater that's less than 10 million years old.]]></description>
