      <title>Rosetta mission: lacking sunlight, Philae lander enters deep sleep</title>
      <description><![CDATA[After landing in a bad spot atop the surface of Comet 67P, the Rosetta mission’s Philae probe has now entered deep sleep as sunlight is unable to reach its solar panels.The landing took an unexpected turn when the probe bounced twice after its first touchdown on Comet 67P on Wednesday. The probe rested on its side against a cliff. Despite not having much energy, Philae managed to transmit important data about Comet 67P back to Earth before its batteries died on Saturday.ESA mission controllers sent commands to the probe to rotate its body in an attempt to expose a larger portion of it to sunlight, but the rotation happened too late to charge the batteries and the lander has since fallen silent, the Guardian reported. Conditions may change as comet 67P moves closer to the sun, which could make it possible for the lander to charge its secondary battery, according to CNN. When it awakes, the Philae may be able to send more data and photos back to Earth.Comet 67P is expected to reach its closest point to the Sun on August 13 2015, a distance of about 185 million kilometers, roughly between the orbits of Earth and Mars.]]></description>
