      <title>Silence held to mark tenth anniversary of London bombings</title>
      <description><![CDATA[A minute's silence was held at several sites in the UK Tuesday to mark the tenth anniversary of the the London Underground and bus bombings of 7 July 2005 in which 52 people were killed.Several underground stations started their silences at 08:50am - the time of the first bomb.The four bombs, three on subway trains and one on a bus, were carried out by four al-Qaeda sympathisers carrying backpacks full of explosivesIt remains the worst terrorist atrocity on British soil.Shezad Tanweer detonated his device on a Circle Line train between Liverpool Street and Aldgate.The explosion at the rear of the train’s second carriage killed seven people.The second suicide bomb exploded on the 311 train travelling south from King’s Cross to Russell Square.Twenty six people were killed when bomber Germaine Lindsay set off his bomb near the second set of double doors of the first carriage.Mohammad Sidique Khan set off his bomb on a Circle Line train as it was leaving Edgware Road station.The bomb, located in the second carriage, killed six people.Almost one hour later Hasib Hussain detonated his bomb on the upper level of a number 30 bus as it travelled through Tavistock Square.The force of the explosion tore the bus apart, killing 13 people.More than 700 others were injured by the explosions.]]></description>
