      <title>Amtrak engineer hit emergency brake before train derailed in Philadelphia, NTSB says</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twAn engineer used an emergency brake moments before Amtrak Train 188 derailed in Philadelphia on Tuesday night at more than 100 miles per hour, according to National Transportation Safety Bureau official Robert Sumwalt, as reported by NBC.At least seven people were killed and more than 200 injured in the derailment.According to Sumwalt, the train was placed into engineered-induced braking moments before the derailment, meaning engineers applied the full emergency braking application. While the maximum speed at the curve was 50 mph, Sumwalt said the train was traveling at 106 mph when the engineer induced the brake application. Three seconds later the train speed was at 102 mph after the brake was applied and then it fully derailed, according to Sumwalt.Amtrak’s Northeast Regional Train 188 derailed Tuesday at around 9.30 p.m. in Philadelphia’s Port Richmond section along the Delaware River. The train was en route from Washington, DC to New York. The accident disrupted services along the Northeast Corridor, which runs from Boston to Washington and is the busiest and most congested passenger railroad in the United States. The Northeast Corridor served 11.6 million passengers in 2014 and has more than 2,200 commuter and freight trains operating from Boston to Washington each day.The train was heading into a bend in the track near Frankford Junction when it went off the tracks at a point where a 70 mph stretch turns into a 50 mph curve. All seven train cars derailed and one of the cars, which separated from the rest, was completely wrecked.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Amtrak train traveling with 238 passengers and five crew from Washington, DC to New York2. Train heading into a bend in the track near Frankford Junction3. Engineer’s cab4. Emergency brake is activated5. Train’s wheels slow6. Train derails7. AftermathVOICEOVER (in English): “Amtrak’s Northeast Regional Train 188 derailed Tuesday night in Philadelphia while en route from Washington, DC to New York carrying 238 passengers and five crew members.” “A National Transportation Safety Board official says an investigation shows an Amtrak engineer applied the emergency brakes just as the train was heading into a bend in the track near Frankford Junction, slowing the locomotive from 106 mph to 102 mph.”“The train went off the tracks at a point where a 70-mph stretch turns into a 50-mph curve.”“All seven train cars derailed, and the engine, which separated from the rest, was completely wrecked.” SOURCES: CNN, Wall Street Journal, Reuters, WCAU, NBC News, CNN, New York Times, Amtrakhttp://edition.cnn.com/2015/05/13/us/philadelphia-amtrak-train-derailment/http://www.wsj.com/articles/deadly-train-wreck-in-philadelphia-leaves-disastrous-mess-1431499608http://uk.reuters.com/article/2015/05/13/uk-usa-train-derailment-idUKKBN0NY04C20150513http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/05/13/us-usa-train-derailment-idUSKBN0NY04E20150513http://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/local/Amtrak-Derailment-Philadelphia--303536331.html?_osource=SocialFlowTwt_PHBrandhttp://www.cnbc.com/id/102673436http://edition.cnn.com/2015/05/13/us/philadelphia-amtrak-train-derailment/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/14/us/amtrak-train-derails-crash-philadelphia.html?_r=0#http://www.amtrak.com/ccurl/238/481/Amtrak-FY2014-Ridership-and-Revenue-ATK-14-096%20.pdfhttp://nec.amtrak.com/facts-and-datahttp://www.wgal.com/news/several-people-injured-in-amtrak-crash/32989264***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
