      <title>Thai police look for &#x201C;foreign suspect&#x201D; after deadly Bangkok shrine bombing</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twThai police have issued an arrest warrant for an “unidentified foreign man” who they believe is the chief suspect in the deadly bombing of Bangkok’s Erawan Shrine.Thai police released a sketch of the chief suspect based on the surveillance video and a description by a motorbike taxi driver who gave the suspect a ride shortly after the explosion, the New York Daily News reported.The suspect reportedly gave the driver a piece of paper with the name of a central city park written in English. The driver said the man also spoke in an unfamiliar language on his phone during the ride, according to CNN.“When I dropped him, he still appeared very calm, just like (a) normal customer. He seemed not in a hurry at all,” Driver Kasem Pooksuwan told CNN.The suspect was caught on camera leaving a backpack at the crowded shrine before the stands up and walks away. Police said the two people seen standing in front him are possible accomplices. The bomb went off just 15 minutes after the suspect left the shrine, according to New York Daily News.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Depiction of Thai police making a sketch of the suspect 2. Suspect leaving a backpack at the shrine3. Two possible accomplices standing in front of him4. Bomb goes off 15 minutes after the suspect leaves the shrine5. The suspect in a motorcycle taxiVOICEOVER (in English): “Thai police composed a sketch of the chief suspect in the bombing of Erawan Shrine based on surveillance video and a description by a motorbike taxi driver who gave the suspect a ride shortly after the explosion.”“The suspect was caught on camera leaving a backpack at the crowded shrine before standing up and walking away. Police said the two people seen standing in front him are possible accomplices.”“The bomb went off 15 minutes after the suspect left the shrine.”“After allegedly planting the bomb, the suspect then hailed a motorbike taxi and gave the driver a piece of paper with the name of a central city park written in English. The driver said he also spoke in an unfamiliar language on his phone during the ride.”SOURCES: CNN, Bangkok Post, New York Daily Newshttp://edition.cnn.com/2015/08/19/asia/thailand-bangkok-bombing/http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/general/660032/police-after-ratchaprasong-bomb-suspecthttp://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/bangkok-bombing-thai-police-issue-arrest-warrant-forei-article-1.2330626***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
