      <title>Airbus lodges patent for &#x2018;stacked&#x2019; airline passenger seating</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFrench airplane maker Airbus has filed patents in Europe and the United States for split-level passenger seating configurations  an idea which has been likened to stacking passengers like blocks.In the document, published with the United States Patent and Trademark Office on October 1, several illustrations depict possible futures wherein flyers would be arranged in alternating rows on upper and lower levels. The document presents the idea as a way to make better use of unused “upper lobe” space in wide-bodied models such as the A380.The economic benefits to airlines are obvious. The proposed seating configurations would allow airlines to fit more people into a plane than they do currently. And with what it calls mezzanine seating, more passengers could recline to a flat-lying position, a setup the patent application suggests would be “suitable” for use in business class sections.But flyers may not be ready for these controversial ideas. Both aviation commentators and the flying public panned the idea of near-standing “saddle” seating when it was revealed in one of the company’s hundreds of patent filings in 2014.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. An Airbus A380 in flight2. Aircraft passenger cabin with two levels; a passenger walking along the aisle3. Passenger on upper level reclines in her seat4. Flight attendant delivering beverage to passenger; passengers on upper  level facing the back of the plane5. Passengers seated on upper level facing each otherVOICEOVER (in English): “Hoping to make better use of unused ‘upper lobe’ space in wide-bodied models such as the A380 ...“… Airbus has filed patents in Europe and the United States for split-level seating  configurations.”“With what the company calls mezzanine seating, more passengers could recline to a flat-lying position.”“The proposed seating configurations would allow airlines to fit more people into a plane than they do currently.”“The economic benefits to airlines are obvious, but flyers may not be ready for these controversial ideas.”SOURCES: United States Patent and Trademark Office, Quartz, News.com.auhttp://pdfaiw.uspto.gov/.aiw?PageNum=0&docid=20150274298&IDKey=0410F6F462F7&HomeUrl=http%3A%2F%2Fappft.uspto.gov%2Fnetacgi%2Fnph-Parser%3FSect1%3DPTO2%2526Sect2%3DHITOFF%2526p%3D1%2526u%3D%25252Fnetahtml%25252FPTO%25252Fsearch-adv.html%2526r%3D1%2526f%3DG%2526l%3D50%2526d%3DPG01%2526S1%3D20150274298%2526OS%3D20150274298%2526RS%3D20150274298http://www.news.com.au/travel/travel-advice/enjoy-the-space-on-planes-while-youve-got-it/story-fn6yjmoc-1227559525929***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
