      <title>Woman sues Honda after airbag severs her throat during car crash</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twA woman has filed a lawsuit against Honda and other companies after an airbag that deployed wrongly during a car crash severely damaged her throat and left her unable to speak, KUTV reported.According to the lawsuit, 25-year-old Randi Johnston was driving her 2003 Honda Civic to work on September 29, when she rear-ended a car in front of her. Her airbag failed failed to deploy properly, instead exploding with shrapnel and causing damage to her neck and head.Earlier this year several car manufacturers, including Honda, recalled nearly 34 million cars over problems with Takata airbags. Inside airbags is an inflator, which is filled with propellant granules and propellants, reported Reuters. Unlike most brands, Takata-designed propellants are made from ammonium nitrate.  If exposed to high humidity, the propellants can end up damaged, which causes them to produce excess pressure inside the inflator, making it crack and explode.During the crash Johnston’s trachea was severed and vocal chords damaged by a piece of shrapnel, reported the Salt Lake Tribune. As a result she cannot currently speak and is suing several corporations including Takata and Honda for her injuries.Johnston can only communicate by writing on a notepad and her family are uncertain if she’ll ever get her voice back, reported KUTV. Currently no court dates have been set for her case.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Car crash 2. Interior view of crash3. Explanation of airbag4. How the inflator may explode5. Johnston’s injuriesVOICEOVER (in English): 25-year-old Randi Johnston was driving her 2003 Honda Civic to work on September 29, when she rear-ended a car in front of her. Her airbag failed to deploy properly, the explosive force sending shrapnel into her head and neck.In May several car manufacturers, including Honda, recalled nearly 34 million cars over problems with Takata airbags. Airbags contain an inflator, which is filled with granules and propellants. Unlike most brands, Takata-designed propellants are made from ammonium nitrate.If exposed to high humidity, the propellants can end up damaged, which causes them to produce excess pressure inside the inflator, making it crack and explode.During the crash, Johnston’s trachea was severed and her vocal chords damaged by a piece of shrapnel. She now cannot speak and is suing Takata, Honda and others for her injuries.SOURCES: Motley Rice LLC, KUTV, Fox 13 Now, Salt Lake Tribune, Reutershttp://www.motleyrice.com/sites/default/files/documents/General/Johnstonv.Takata-Filed_Complaint.pdfhttp://kutv.com/news/local/utah-family-joins-airbag-lawsuit-after-shrapnel-almost-kills-daughterhttp://fox13now.com/2015/11/11/centerville-woman-sues-after-airbag-malfunction-severs-her-trachea-and-vocal-chords/http://www.sltrib.com/home/3166129-155/utah-woman-sues-honda-local-dealershiphttp://www.reuters.com/article/2015/10/20/us-autos-takata-rosekind-idUSKCN0SD1VO20151020http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/06/25/us-autos-takata-idUSKBN0P503D20150625***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
