      <title>Aerospace firm patents solar window shade that can charge electronic devices</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twB/E Aerospace has filed a patent for a solar window shade that can charge electronic devices in an airplane.The device is designed with solar panels on the outer surface to receive sunlight, which would convert solar energy into power. The shades, which would be equipped with wired or wireless charging ports, would allow passengers to directly plug in their devices.The high tech window shade weighs only slightly more than an ordinary window shade (29-50 grams), according to B/E Aerospace. The company also claims it will actually “generate more energy than the extra fuel required” to carry it.B/E Aerospace says a single 737 making six 1000 nautical mile trips everyday would save around $22,000, conserve over 7300 gallons of fuel per year, and reduce 154,000 pounds of CO2 emissions.Modern planes that are equipped with traditional power points or USB outlets are powered by the plane’s internal electrical system. These systems require long lengths of wiring and interconnections, which add significant cost and weight to the interior construction of the plane, B/E Aerospace says.B/E Aerospace’s patent filing states the shade could easily be adapted for use on current airplanes or other aircraft, and requires no change to the rest of a cabin’s components.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Solar panel window shade charging2. Passenger charging electronic devices through window shade3. Weight comparison between old and new window shade4. Savings for airlines using new window shades5. Traditional electric wiring increasing costs for airlinesVOICEOVER (in English): “B/E Aerospace has filed a patent for airplane wi ndow shades that are equipped with solar panels.”“The solar cells integrated into the window shades harness energy from the sun and turn it into power passengers can charge their electronic devices with.”“The company claims these new devices would only weigh slightly more than ordinary window shades …”“ … and generate more energy than the extra fuel required to carry them. These devices would allow airlines to save money, conserve fuel, and reduce CO2 emissions.”“Modern planes equipped with traditional power points or USB outlets that are powered by the plane’s electrical system require long lengths of wiring that end up being costly.”SOURCES: DAILY MAIL, SKIFThttp://www.dailymail.co.uk/travel/travel_news/article-3617817/Plane-window-shade-charge-passengers-phones.htmlhttps://skift.com/2015/04/17/this-eco-friendly-airplane-window-shade-could-be-your-smartphones-new-best-friend/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
