      <title>Luxury cruise ship Crystal Serenity prepares to enter Arctic waters</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twHigh-end tourism came to one of the last wildernesses on the planet on Tuesday, when a huge luxury cruise ship entered Arctic waters.The Crystal Serenity is 82 feet long and weighs more than 68,000 tons. The ship is carrying around 1,000 passengers, who have each paid upwards of $22,000 for a trip only made possible by the melting of ice in the notoriously treacherous waters of the Northwest Passage linking the Pacific and northern Atlantic oceans.The ship left Seward, Alaska last week and docked in the city of Nome on Monday, its last stop before entering Arctic waters, Crystal Berg reported.The ship’s sold-out voyage has raised concerns among the green lobby, who believe it is taking advantage of climate change and could lead to environmental damage in the Arctic by opening the gates to more cruise ships.The Crystal Serenity is accompanied by an ice-breaking boat and two helicopters. The ship is expected to stop in Greenland as it makes its way through the Northwest Passage to New York.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Crystal Serenity carrying 1,000 tourists paying at least $22,000 each2. Route of ship from Seward to Nome, Alaska3. Crystal Serenity accompanied by ice-breaking ship and two helicopters4. Route of ship from Nome to New YorkVOICEOVER (in English): “The Crystal Serenity is carrying around 1,000 passengers, who have each paid upwards of $22,000 for the trip.”“The ship left Seward, Alaska last week and docked in the city of Nome on Monday, its last stop before entering Arctic waters.”“The Crystal Serenity is accompanied by an ice-breaking boat and two helicopters.”“The ship is expected to stop in Greenland as it makes its way through the Northwest Passage to New York.”SOURCES: Washington Post, Capital Berg, Arctic Journalhttps://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2016/08/16/a-luxury-cruise-ship-sets-sail-for-the-arctic-thanks-to-climate-change/?tid=pm_business_pop_b&utm_term=.4a863bbc7d5ehttp://www.capitalberg.com/crystal-serenity-arrives-nome/29867/http://arcticjournal.com/business/2527/destination-uncertain***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
