      <title>FDA approves &#x2018;abdominal vomiting&#x2019; weight-loss device</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twThe United States Food and Drug Administration (FDA) has approved a weight loss device that uses an external pump to drain stomach contents into the toilet.The device, known as the AspireAssist, is manufactured by Pennsylvania company Aspire Bariatrics. It is roughly the size of a smartphone and can be easily stored in a small bag.AspireAssist is connected to a port on the user’s stomach, which is installed via surgery. The food flows into a pre-installed tube inside the stomach into the device once the lever is switched on, and drains directly into the toilet.The user can pump some water into the stomach with the device’s reservoir to loosen the food particles inside the stomach when experiencing blockage.The company says only a third of the food will be drained, so that the body still has enough calories to function.The device has been called “assisted bulimia” by some critics. Its side effects include nausea, vomiting, constipation and diarrhea.The latest data from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention shows that 38 percent of American adults and 17 percent of teenagers are obese.The FDA has approved AspireAssist to be used on adults with a body mass index of 35 to 55 who have not been able to lose weight with other methods. Clinical results show the device has helped users to lose an average of over 12 percent of their body weight.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Size of AspireAssist in comparison to a smartphone; the device worn on a medical body2. The port of the device connected to the stomach; the lever switched on and food starts to flow into the tube3. The food is drained into the toilet4. Water pumped back into the stomach to allow more food to be drained5. Two thirds of the food is digested to provide energy to the body6. Depiction of 38% of American adults are obese; AspireAssist helps to lose about 12% body weight with side effects of vomiting and constipationVOICEOVER (in English): “AspireAssist is roughly the size of a smartphone and can be easily stored in a small bag. An extended string allows the device to be worn on the body.”“The device is connected to a port on the user’s stomach. The food flows into a pre-installed tube inside the stomach into the device once the lever is switched on.”“The food is drained directly into the toilet.”“The user can pump some water into the stomach with the device’s reservoir to loosen food particles inside the stomach when experiencing a blockage.”“Only a third of the food will be drained, so that the body still has enough calories to function.”“Data shows 38% of American adults are obese. The developers of AspireAssist claim the device has helped users lose an average of at least 12% body weight, despite side effects such as vomiting and constipation.”SOURCES: Aspire Bariatrics, The Morning Call, AJC.com, NBC Newshttp://www.aspirebariatrics.com/about-the-aspireassist/http://www.mcall.com/news/nationworld/pennsylvania/mc-pa-fda-weight-loss-device-0615-20160615-story.htmlhttp://www.ajc.com/ap/ap/pennsylvania/fda-approves-stomach-draining-obesity-treatment/nrgJb/http://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/fda-approves-weight-loss-stomach-pump-aspireassist-combat-obesity-n592141***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
