      <title>Carbon dioxide turned to stone in Iceland climate change experiment</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twResearchers are hailing a potential game-changer for climate change after successfully converting carbon to rock at a geothermal power plant in Iceland.The project could help to reduce global warming by burying the waste CO2 produced from burning fossil fuels, the Guardian reported.Scientists at the Hellisheidi geothermal power plant converted carbon dioxide into the volcanic rock basalt, according to a study published in the journal Science.The researchers pumped 230 tons of CO2 into rock 500 meters underground, dissolving the gas in water to prevent it from escaping. More than 95 percent of the gas turned to stone within two years, speeding up a natural process that takes hundreds or thousands of years, the Guardian reported.A potential problem for the technique is that it requires 25 tons of water for every ton of buried CO2. However, researchers said seawater can be used, which is abundant at coastal sites, the Guardian reported.The project is seen as an improvement on existing carbon capture and storage methods that store CO2 as a gas, causing concern about potential leaks.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Map of Iceland; location of Hellisheidi power plant2. Carbon dioxide and water pumped into basalt 500 meters beneath the earth3. Carbon dioxide reacts with basalt, turns into rock4. Comparison of 25 tons of water required to convert 1 tonne of carbon dioxideVOICEOVER (in English): “Scientists at the Hellisheidi geothermal power plant in Iceland have converted carbon dioxide into the volcanic rock basalt.”“Researchers pumped 230 tonnes of CO2 into rock 500 meters underground, dissolving the gas in water to prevent it from escaping.” “More than 95 percent of the gas turned to stone within two years, speeding up a natural process that takes hundreds or thousands of years.”“A potential problem for the technique is that it requires 25 tons of water for every ton of buried CO2.”SOURCES: Science Magazine, The Guardianhttp://science.sciencemag.org/content/352/6291/1312.fullhttp://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/jun/09/co2-turned-into-stone-in-iceland-in-climate-change-breakthrough***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
