      <title>Study finds Zika virus infects fetus via the placenta</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twResearchers claim they have discovered why the Zika virus infects unborn children via the mother’s placenta in a new study.The placenta usually sustains the fetus, providing nourishment and defending it against infections. But in the case of the Zika Virus, a new study has found that the placenta appears to enhance the disease’s growth.According to the Atlanta Journal Constitution, the team of  Emory University researchers found that the Zika virus infects immune cells in the placenta and replicates there without killing the host cell. From there virus travels deeper inside the fetus, eventually infecting the unborn child.The study was published last Friday in the journal Cell Host Microbe.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. How the placenta traditionally works2. The Zika virus passing through the placenta3. The Zika virus replicating via the placenta’s immune cells 4. An unborn child being infected with the Zika virusVOICEOVER (in English): "The placenta usually sustains the fetus, providing nourishment and defending it against infections. However, in the case of the Zika virus, a new study has found that the placenta appears to enhance the disease’s growth." "Emory University researchers found that the Zika virus infects immune cells in the placenta and replicates without killing the host cell. From there, the virus travels deeper inside the fetus, eventually infecting the unborn child."SOURCES: Atlanta Journal Constitution, Science 20, Science Dailyhttp://www.ajc.com/news/news/local/emory-researchers-show-how-zika-may-infect-placent/nrWJ8/http://www.science20.com/news_articles/how_zika_infects_the_placenta-173613https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2016/05/160527133335.htm***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
