      <title>Drone-satellite hybrid to conduct surveillance from Earth&#x2019;s stratosphere</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twThales Alenia Space is building a revolutionary Zeppelin-like airship designed for applications ranging from border surveillance to environmental management, according to a recent press statement released by the Cannes-based aerospace manufacturer.The Stratobus, made mainly of UV-resistant carbon fiber, will measure 70 to 100 meters long and 20 to 30 meters wide.Reaching an altitude of 20 kilometers in the atmosphere, which is higher than most aircraft, the Stratobus will have a view range of about 500 kilometers. Reaching this height allows the airship to serve a similar function as satellites do currently, including border and maritime surveillance, telecommunications, broadcasting and navigation, reported Phys.org.According to Thales Alenia Space, a ring around the Stratobus allows the airship to rotate and face the Sun no matter the season or time of day. After solar rays enter the airship through a transparent section of the outer envelope, the rays reflect off a mirror inside and onto a row of solar panels. Energy collected from the solar panels is then sent to the Stratobus’ nacelle where the airship’s ultra-light fuel cell and electrolyzer are both located. The fuel cell stores the energy used by the spaceship, while the electrolyzer converts water onboard into gas.Despite the high winds at these altitudes, two fuel-cell powered electric motors at the sides of the airship maintain the airship’s stability.While this idea has been in the works for some time, Thales recently announced the official launch of the project in April, which will have 24 development phases. The prototype will be ready for testing in 2018, and the airships are expected to become commercialized by 2020.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Length and width of the Stratobus2. The Stratobus will reach an altitude of 20 kilometers3. A ring located on the Stratobus allows the airship to spin and face the Sun4. Solar rays bounce off mirrors within the airship and hit solar panels inside5. Energy collected from the panels is sent to the airship’s nacelle6. The fuel cell and electrolyzer are located in the nacelle; they store energy7. Two electric motors maintain the airship’s stability while in air 8. The Stratobus has a view range of about 500 kilometersVOICEOVER (in English): “The Stratobus, made mainly of UV-resistant carbon fiber, will measure 70 to 100 meters long and 20 to 30 meters wide.” “Designed by Thales Alenia Space, the airship will be able to reach the stratosphere and soar to an altitude of 20 kilometers, higher than most aircraft.”“A ring around the Stratobus allows the airship to rotate and face the Sun no matter the season or time of day.”“Solar rays enter the airship through a transparent section of the outer envelope. The rays then reflect off a mirror inside and onto a row of solar panels.”“Energy collected from the solar panels is sent to the Stratobus’ nacelle, the section located under the airship’s main body.”“A fuel cell and electrolyzer are located in the nacelle. The fuel cell stores the energy used by the spaceship, while the electrolyzer converts water onboard into gas.”“Despite the strong winds at these altitudes, two fuel-cell powered electric motors at the sides of the airship are able to maintain the airship’s stability.”“Hovering within the stratosphere, the Stratobus has a view range of about 500 kilometers.”SOURCES: Thales Group, Phys.org, Gizmaghttps://www.thalesgroup.com/en/worldwide/space/press-release/stratobus-project-takeshttp://phys.org/news/2014-03-stratobus-airship-prototype-years-video.html#ajTabshttp://www.gizmag.com/thales-alenia-space-stratobus-airship/31395/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
