      <title>Superflares may have sparked life on Earth</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twNew research suggests solar storms from a young Sun helped kickstart life on Earth.NASA reports that some 4 billion years ago, only 70 percent of the Sun’s energy was received by the Earth  not enough to warm the planet. Despite this, geological evidence shows our planet was a warm globe with liquid water. Scientists have long been puzzled by this, calling it the Faint Young Sun Paradox. But now there may finally be an explanation: superflares.Researchers from NASA’s Goddard Space Flight Center pieced together a timeline of the Sun’s evolution by analyzing data from NASA’s Kepler space telescope, which found stars resembling our Sun.Our Sun today produces superflares once every 100 years. The bulk of this energy is kept from reaching Earth by the planet’s strong magnetic field.When the Sun was much younger  only a few million years old  the flares were much more frequent and intense. The Earth then had a weaker magnetic field, allowing particles from solar storms to collide with nitrogen molecules in the atmosphere, breaking them into individual atoms. These, in turn, split carbon dioxide molecules into carbon monoxide and oxygen.Nitrogen combined with oxygen to form nitrous oxide, a potent greenhouse gas that would have warmed the planet enough for liquid water to exist. Energy from the solar particles may have also helped create complex compounds like DNA and RNA  the building blocks of life.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Earth’s strong magnetic field helps protect from solar flares2. Young Sun had more powerful and frequent flares; young Earth had a less powerful magnetic field3. Flares changed the chemistry of Earth’s atmosphere4. Nitrous oxide warmed Earth5. Solar energy helped create DNA and RNA that produced lifeVOICEOVER (in English): “Our Sun today produces superflares once every 100 years. The bulk of this energy is kept from reaching Earth by the planet’s strong magnetic field.”“When the Sun was much younger  only a few million years old  the flares were much more frequent and intense. The Earth then also had a weaker magnetic field.”“Particles from solar storms collided with nitrogen molecules in the atmosphere, breaking them into individual atoms. These, in turn, split carbon dioxide molecules into carbon monoxide and oxygen.”“Nitrogen combined with oxygen to form nitrous oxide, a potent greenhouse gas that would have warmed the planet enough for liquid water to exist.”“Energy from the solar particles may have also helped create complex compounds like DNA and RNA  the building blocks of life.”SOURCES: NASA, Washington Posthttp://www.nasa.gov/feature/goddard/2016/nasa-solar-storms-may-have-been-key-to-life-on-earthhttps://www.washingtonpost.com/news/speaking-of-science/wp/2016/05/23/a-violent-sun-and-a-sky-full-of-laughing-gas-could-have-led-to-life-on-earth/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
