      <title>World&#x2019;s largest cruise ship Harmony of the Seas sets sail on maiden voyage</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twThe largest cruise ship ever built arrived in the English port of Southampton on Tuesday, ready to set sail on its maiden voyage.At 362 meters in length, cruise line Royal Caribbean International’s Harmony of the Seas is a full 100 meters longer than the Titanic, according to the Daily Mail. Its length is the equivalent of four football pitches, the BBC reported. The ship has a passenger capacity of 6,780. It has 20 restaurants, 23 swimming pools, a 10-storey waterslide, two surf simulators, two rock-climbing walls, a full-sized basketball court and an ice-skating rink.“Harmony of the Seas is the world's largest cruise ship. Bigger can be beautiful when it allows you to put so many great facilities on board to allow people to have a great holiday at sea,” Stuart Leven, the managing director for the UK and Ireland of Royal Caribbean International told the Telegraph.One of the key feature of the ship is its bionic bar. Passengers can place drink orders via an app and robotic arms mix and serve the drinks. The two arms can make two drinks per minute.Passengers are given a wristband known as the WOWband, which acts as a room key and can be used to pay for dinner and shopping onboard.Harmony of the Seas is the 25th ship in Royal Caribbean International’s fleet. It cost $1 billion and took two and a half years to build.The ship will leave Southampton for Rotterdam on May 22 on a four-night cruise, the BBC reported. It will then sail to Barcelona, Marseille, Florence, Rome and Naples.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Harmony of the Sea in comparison to the Eiffel Tower; depiction of passenger capacity2. Depiction of the facilities on the ship3. Customer ordering drinks at bionic bar; bionic arms make 2 drinks per minute4. Customer opening door with a band; customer pay with the band5. Sailing route of Harmony of the SeasVOICEOVER (in English): “At 362 meters long, Harmony of the Seas is longer than the height of the Eiffel Tower, and can hold 6,780 passengers.”“Among the ship’s many facilities are 20 restaurants, 23 swimming pools, a full-sized basketball court and an ice-skating rink.”“Robotic arms at the ship’s bionic bar can mix and serve two drinks per minute.”“Passengers are given a wristband, known as the WOWband, which works as a room key and can be used to pay for dinner and shopping onboard.”“The ship will leave Southampton for Rotterdam on May 22. It will then sail to ports in Spain, France and Italy.”SOURCES: The Telegraph, BBC, CBS News, Royal Caribbean Internationalhttp://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/05/17/worlds-largest-cruise-ship-harmony-of-the-seas-arrives-in-southa/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-hampshire-36304174http://www.cbsnews.com/news/harmony-of-the-seas-worlds-largest-cruise-ship-makes-maiden-voyage/http://www.royalcaribbean.com/harmonyoftheseas/staterooms/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
