      <title>Reducing U.S. carbon emissions now may prevent 295,000 deaths by 2030</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twAccording to a team of researchers from Duke University and the NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, slashing carbon emissions won’t just reduce global warming, it could also prevent tens of thousands of premature deaths by 2030.A 2-degree Celsius increase in atmospheric warming is usually considered the threshold at which the changes brought about by global warming  such as droughts and flooding  could exceed our ability to adapt. According to their research paper published in Nature earlier this week, researchers say that the two largest sources of pollutants responsible for climate change in the United States are the transportation and energy sectors. The carbon emissions attributed to climate change are not just bad for the environment, they also have negative consequences for human health.In their study, researchers modeled what would happen if emissions in both sectors were reduced enough by 2030 to put the U.S. on the path to stay under the 2-degree Celsius threshold.By 2030, under this “cleaner energy” scenario, as many as 175,000 premature deaths were prevented in the U.S., and another 22,000 deaths were prevented every following year. Under a “cleaner transportation” scenario, as many as 120,000 premature deaths were prevented, and another 14,000 deaths were prevented each following year.The nationwide health benefits of reducing carbon emissions would total around $250 billion a year  far exceeding the cost of implementing new policies.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Two-degree Celsius rise in atmospheric warming and its global impact 2. Two largest sources of greenhouse emissions in the U.S. are the transportation and energy sectors3. Researchers model the impact of significantly reducing emissions4. Reductions prevent global temperatures from rising more than 2 degrees Celsius5. Cleaner energy policies prevent more than 175,000 premature deaths 6. Cleaner transportation policies prevent more than 120,000 premature deaths VOICEOVER (in English): “A 2-degree Celsius increase in atmospheric warming is usually considered the threshold at which the changes brought about by climate change, for instance drought, flooding, declining fish populations and the spread of tropical diseases, are more than humans could handle.”“The two largest sources of pollutants responsible for climate change in the United States are the transportation and energy sectors.’’“In a research paper published in Nature, researchers modeled what would happen if emissions in both sectors are significantly reduced by 2030.”“In their study, the researchers reduced the emissions in both sectors enough to put the U.S. on the path to stay under the 2-degree Celsius threshold.”“By 2030, under this ‘cleaner energy’ scenario, as many as 175,000 premature deaths were prevented in the U.S. and another 22,000 deaths were prevented every following year.”“Under a ‘cleaner transportation’ scenario, as many as 120,000 premature deaths in the U.S. were prevented and another 14,000 deaths were prevented each following year.”SOURCES: Nature, Duke University, Tech Times, The Huffington Posthttp://www.nature.com/nclimate/journal/vaop/ncurrent/full/nclimate2935.htmlhttps://nicholas.duke.edu/about/news/lowcarbonpols-cutdeathsby2030http://www.techtimes.com/articles/135872/20160223/reducing-us-carbon-emissions-may-prevent-295-000-deaths-by-2030.htmhttp://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/cutting-carbon-emissions-could-save-175000-lives_us_56cc91bfe4b0928f5a6d52a1***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
