      <title>Seas rising at fastest rate in 2,800 years</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twA new study shows that sea level is rising at a speed that is faster than the previous 27 centuries.Sea level rose at a rate of 1.4 millimeters per year between 1900 and 2000 while the current rate is 3.4 millimeters per year, according to data provided by NASA.The study, led by Robert Kopp, a professor of earth and planetary sciences at Rutgers University, shows that although it is impossible to slow the rate of sea level rise to what it was in the 20th century, a low carbon dioxide emissions scenario would make it more likely than a high carbon dioxide emission scenario.The study, published on Monday in the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, also points out that the major factor in future sea level rises is the melting of the huge ice sheets of Greenland and Antarctica.The study was based on earlier sea level rises at 24 locations around the world, as well as recent measurements from 66 global tide gauges.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Speed of sea level rising between 1850 to 2100; depiction of global warming as the cause2. Depiction of sea level rises slower in low carbon dioxide emissions scenario3. Depiction of huge ice sheets in Greenland and Antarctica contributing to sea level risingVOICEOVER (in English): “Owing to global warming,  sea levels rose at a rate of 1.4 millimeters per year between 1900 to 2000 while the current level is 3.4 millimeters per year.“Though it’s impossible to slow the rate of sea level rise to what it was in the 20th century, a lower carbon dioxide emissions scenario would assist in arresting the rate at which the sea level is rising.” “Researchers said the major factor in future sea level rise is the melting of the huge ice sheets of Greenland and Antarctica.”SOURCES: The Washington Post, New York Times, NASA, P Rutgers Universityhttps://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2016/02/22/seas-are-now-rising-faster-than-they-have-in-2800-years-scientists-say/http://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/23/science/sea-level-rise-global-warming-climate-change.html?_r=0https://sealevel.nasa.gov/multimediahttp://www.pnas.org/content/early/2016/02/17/1517056113.fullhttp://news.rutgers.edu/news-release/sea-level-rise-accelerating-faster-thought/20150115#.VsvjnoSIdX8***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
