      <title>More than 18,300 Americans apply to be NASA astronauts, smashing records</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twOver the past two months, tens of thousands of Americans who hope to help blaze a trail to Mars and beyond submitted applications for NASA’s 2017 astronaut class. Between mid-December and mid-February, a record-breaking 18,300 applicants applied for eight to 14 spots in NASA’s astronaut candidate program this year. NASA received almost three times the number of applicants the space agency received during its last round of hiring in 2012, shattering the previous record of 8,000 applicants in 1978.NASA’s Astronaut Selection Board will review all of the applications and narrow them down before the top applicants are interviewed at the Johnson Space Center in Houston, Texas, reported Space.com. NASA will select final candidates based on their work experiences, teamwork and communication abilities, as well as particular personality traits.According NASA’s press release, accepted candidates will go through a two-year program where they’ll learn spacecraft systems, teamwork, the Russian language and vital skills  like spacewalking.Once they graduate, astronauts will be assigned to any of the four different spacecraft: the International Space Station, NASA’s Orion aircraft, the Boeing CST-100 Starliner or the SpaceX Crew Dragon.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Number of applicants to NASA’s astronaut candidate program; number of openings2. Applicants narrowed down; top applicants interviewed at the space station3. Selection criteria4. Astronaut candidates go through a two-year training process5. Where the astronauts will be assigned following their trainingVOICEOVER (in English): “A record-breaking 18,300 applicants have applied for 14 or fewer spots in NASA’s astronaut candidate program this year.”“The applicants will first be narrowed down before the top applicants are interviewed at the Johnson Space Center in Houston, Texas.”“NASA will select candidates based on their work experiences, teamwork and communication abilities, as well as particular personality traits.”“Accepted candidates will go through a two-year program where they’ll learn spacecraft systems, teamwork, the Russian language and vital skills  like spacewalking.”“Astronauts who finish the program will be assigned to the International Space Station, NASA’s Orion aircraft, the Boeing CST-100 Starliner or the SpaceX Crew Dragon.”SOURCES: Discovery, NASA, Space.comhttp://news.discovery.com/space/record-18300-apply-for-nasa-astronaut-training-160221.htmhttp://astronauts.nasa.gov/content/faq.htmhttp://astronauts.nasa.gov/content/broch00.htmhttp://astronauts.nasa.gov/content/timeline.htmhttp://www.space.com/31987-nasa-astronaut-applications-smash-record.html***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
