      <title>Why flights between New York City and London may soon get even longer</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twA recent study by researchers at the University of Reading says flights between New York and London could lengthen because of changes to meteorological conditions in the atmosphere that affect the jet stream.The study was published this week in the journal Environmental Research Letters and led by Dr. Paul Williams, an atmosphere scientist at the University of Reading.Researchers say that as the atmosphere warms up due to global warming, the jet stream will become 15 percent faster during winter time, reported Phys.org. The stronger jet stream will boost tailwinds, which may cause flights from New York to London to be shorter than the current five hours and twenty minutes. However, flights from London to New York are going against the jet stream. So trips may take more than seven hours, making the overall round trip longer.Flights are expected to take a total of 2,000 hours longer each year, which means higher fuel costs and more CO2 emissions. According to the study, the extra 2,000 hours each year could burn an extra 7.2 million gallons of jet fuel and emit an extra 70 million kilograms of CO2  equivalent to the annual CO2 output of 7,100 British households.Scientists say that since this jet stream circles the globe and because there’s another in the southern hemisphere, it’s possible that flights elsewhere in the world will be impacted by climate change.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Flightpath between New York and London; plane in the troposphere2. Troposphere warming up and the jetstream moving faster as a result3. Flights from New York to London may become shorter4. Flights from London to New York may become longer; overall trip is longer5. Trips will be longer, which means fuel costs and CO2 emissions will be more6. Amount of CO2 emitted is equivalent to the annual emissions of 7,100 British homesVOICEOVER (in English): “Why flights between London and New York may soon be longer.”“Flights between New York and London could lengthen in response to changes in meteorological conditions in the atmosphere that affect the jet stream.”“Researchers say that as the atmosphere warms up due to global warming, the jet stream will become 15 percent faster during winter time.”“The stronger jet stream will boost tailwinds, which may cause flights from New York to London to be shorter than the current five hours and twenty minutes.”“However, flights from London to New York are going against the jet stream, so trips may take more than seven hours, making the overall round trip longer.”“Flights are expected to take a total of 2,000 hours longer each year, which means higher fuel costs and more CO2 emissions.”“The estimated increase in amount of CO2 emissions is equivalent to the annual CO2 output of 7,100 British homes.”SOURCES: IOP Science, Newser, Phys.orghttp://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/1748-9326/11/2/024008http://www.newser.com/story/220356/flights-from-london-to-new-york-may-get-longer.htmlhttp://phys.org/news/2016-02-climate-transatlantic-flights.html***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
