      <title>North Korea&#x2019;s hydrogen bomb test claim sparks scepticism</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twNorth Korea this week said it had successfully tested a miniaturized hydrogen bomb at the Punggye-ri nuclear test site, but the claim has been met by international skepticism.There are four common techniques to monitor nuclear blasts, Reuters reported, citing the Comprehensive Nuclear-Test Ban Treaty Organization (CTBTO). One of which is seismic technology, which monitors geological activity such as earthquakes. Multiple seismic monitoring stations detected a 5.1 earthquake near the test location  the Punggye-ri nuclear test site. Other techniques include hydroacoustic monitoring which investigates underwater explosions, and infrasound monitoring which measures atmospheric nuclear blasts. A key verification technique is radionuclide monitoring which determines what particles and gases are left in the atmosphere.  According to Reuters, verifying Pyongyang’s most recent claim of a hydrogen bomb would require the presence of tritium and lithium.“If they find lithium, then it's definitely a hydrogen bomb test, but if it's only xenon ... then you're not going to know,” Reuters quoted Shin Kyung-min, a member of South Korea's parliamentary intelligence committee as saying.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Depiction of four methods to monitor nuclear blasts2. Depiction of seismic monitoring; 5.1 earthquake detected near Punggye-ri nuclear test site3. Depiction of hydroacoustic monitoring4. Depiction of infrasound monitoring5. Depiction of radionuclide monitoring; presence of hydrogen isotope tritium in the airVOICEOVER (in English): “Experts employ four common techniques to determine if an atomic or hydrogen bomb has been tested. The first is seismic monitoring.”“Monitoring stations did detect an earthquake measuring 5.1 near Punggye-ri, the site where North Korea has previously tested atomic weapons.”“Hydroacoustic monitoring is used to investigate underwater detonations.”“While infrasound monitoring measures any atmospheric nuclear blasts.”“Another key verification technique is radionuclide monitoring. This detects what particles and gases are in the atmosphere. “Verifying Pyongyang's hydrogen bomb test claim would require the presence of Trillium and lithium in the atmosphere.”SOURCES: Reuters, New York Times, CNN, CTBTOhttp://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-nuclear-test-factbox-idUSKBN0UK2B320160106http://www.reuters.com/article/northkorea-nuclear-detection-idUSKBN0UK21B20160106http://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/07/world/asia/north-korea-hydrogen-bomb-q-a.html?_r=0http://edition.cnn.com/2016/01/06/asia/north-korea-bomb-test-key-questions/index.htmlhttps://www.ctbto.org/the-treaty/developments-after-1996/2016-dprk-announced-nuclear-test/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
