      <title>Lyft&#x2019;s vision for an on-demand network of self-driving cars will mean fewer cars on the road</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twLyft, an American ride-hailing service, announced on Monday that General Motors has invested $500 million in the company, and the companies together plan to develop a network of autonomous vehicles.From the proposed plan, self-driving cars would reach American consumers through a ride-sharing service first rather than through individual ownership. According to a study by IHS Automotive, car ownership in the United States has crept to nearly 258 million vehicles as of 2015. Lyft and General Motors hope to change this through an on-demand network of self-driving cars. Forbes cites a Harvard Health Watch study that says the average American drives almost two hours a day. Even if self-driving cars takes up to half a day for maintenance and to recharge, that still gives users 12 hours a day to use one vehicle  enough time for six Americans to use the car. If six people can use one car, this means the 258 million vehicles on the road could potentially be reduced to around 43 million, or one-sixth of 258 million. The approximately 258 million vehicles registered in the United States are not all owned by different individuals. Some people own more than one car, which means the number of hours cars are left sitting idle is probably even greater.Reuters reports that the two companies haven’t set out a deadline for when the on-demand network would be available to consumers, but would immediately offer Lyft users short term rentals of GM cars. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Number of passenger vehicles in the United States2. Average American only drives two hours a day, leaving his car idle for 22 hours3. Lots of vehicles in the United States are idle through much of the day4. Six people could use one of Lyft’s on-demand cars5. How using on-demand vehicles would cut down on number of cars total6. If carpooling was used, how this would cut down the number of cars even moreVOICEOVER (in English): “Car ownership in the U.S. had crept to nearly 258 million vehicles as of 2015. Lyft and General Motors hope to change this through an on-demand network of self-driving cars.”“The average American drives almost two hours a day and leaves his car idle for the remainder of the day.”“This potentially means that all 258 million vehicles in the U.S. could be idle for an estimated 5.67 billion hours each day.” “Even if a self-driving requires up to half a day for maintenance, that still gives users 12 hours a day to use one vehicle  enough time for six Americans to use the car.” “If six people can use one car, this means the 258 million vehicles on the road could potentially be reduced to around 43 million, or one-sixth of 258 million.”“If people carpool, the amount of cars on the road becomes even less.”SOURCES: The New York Times, Reuters, IHS Automotive, Wired, Forbeshttp://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/05/technology/gm-invests-in-lyft.html?_r=1http://www.reuters.com/article/us-gm-lyft-investment-idUSKBN0UI1A820160104http://press.ihs.com/press-release/automotive/average-age-light-vehicles-us-rises-slightly-2015-115-years-ihs-reportshttp://www.wired.com/2016/01/gm-and-lyft-are-building-a-network-of-self-driving-cars/http://www.forbes.com/sites/stevenrosenbaum/2015/02/26/the-future-of-tv-is-mobile-and-not-the-way-you-think/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
