      <title>U.S. repeals labeling law for pork and beef products</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twUnder country of origin labelling, or COOL, retailers are required to notify customers about the origin of certain foods. Muscle cuts of beef and pork, as well as ground beef and pork were recently removed from the program.According to the U.S. Department of Agriculture, this includes muscle cuts and ground meat of lamb, goat and chicken, as well as farm-raised fish and shellfish. Fresh and frozen fruit as well as vegetables such as peanuts,  pecans, macadamia nuts and ginseng are also on the COOL list. However, the U.S. Department of Agriculture recently removed muscle cuts of pork and beef and ground pork and beef from this list. The removal is the result of an international trade dispute Canada and Mexico brought against the U.S, reported Forbes.In its verdict, the World Trade Organization ruled that the United States’ labelling program discriminated against foreign livestock, reported Forbes.According to the Chicago Tribune, supporters of COOL say it encourages purchases of American meat and is safer, as consumers can know the product’s origin. Those opposed say tracking and labelling is expensive. Additionally, not repealing the law could have resulted in over US$1.1 billion in retaliatory trade tariffs being levied against the U.S, reported the Chicago Tribune.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Explanation of country of origin labelling2. Meats labelled under COOL3. Removal of pork and beef from COOL4. Map view of trade dispute5. Consumer selecting U.S. meat6. Potential retaliatory tariffs against the U.S. VOICEOVER (in English): "With country of origin labelling or COOL for short, retailers are required to notify customers about the origin of certain foods.""This includes muscle cuts, ground lamb, goat and chicken meat, as well as farm-raised fish and shellfish. Fresh and frozen fruit as well as vegetables such as peanuts,  pecans, macadamia nuts and ginseng are also on the COOL list.""But, the U.S. Department of Agriculture recently removed muscle cuts of pork and beef and ground pork and beef from this list.""The removal is the result of an international trade dispute Canada and Mexico brought against the U.S.""In its verdict, the World Trade Organization ruled that the United States’ labelling program discriminated against foreign livestock and violated international trade regulations.""Supporters of food source labelling say it encourages purchases of American-bred meat and is safer, as consumers can know a product’s origin.""Those opposed say tracking and labelling is prohibitively expensive. Additionally, not repealing the law could have resulted in over a US$1.1 billion in retaliatory trade tariffs being levied against the U.S."SOURCES: U.S. Department of Agriculture, Chicago Tribune, World Trade Organization, Forbes, Merritt Herald, Reutershttp://www.ams.usda.gov/rules-regulations/coolhttp://www.chicagotribune.com/dining/ct-cool-country-origin-labeling-food-1223-20160104-story.htmlhttps://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/dispu_e/cases_e/1pagesum_e/ds384sum_e.pdfhttp://www.forbes.com/sites/nancyhuehnergarth/2015/12/21/quashing-consumers-right-to-know-congress-repeals-country-of-origin-labeling-for-beef-and-pork/http://www.merrittherald.com/1b-retaliatory-sanctions-approved-by-wto/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-congress-fiscal-canada-idUSKBN0TZ2T420151216***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
