      <title>Hoverboards grounded by several U.S. airlines due to fire risk</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twHoverboards are fast becoming one of most wanted items this Christmas, but due to safety fears the devices have been banned by several airlines.According to Reuters, passengers will no longer be able to carry hoverboards in their carry on or checked baggage on flights from Delta Airlines, American Airlines and United Airlines. The devices are also known self balancing scooters, or swegways.Reports indicate that some hoverboards have caught on fire or have exploded due to overcharged lithium-ion batteries. Airlines fear that hoverboards may pose a fire risk while onboard an aircraft, Reuters reported.In the UK, authorities found that 88% of 17,000 hoverboards examined at British entry points were unsafe and at risk of overheating, exploding or catching on fire, Reuters reported. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Airlines that have prohibited hoverboards2. Baggage3. Hoverboard overcharging4. Hoverboard on a plane5. Hoverboard risk in the UKVOICEOVER (in English): "Hoverboards are fast becoming one of most wanted items this Christmas, but due to safety fears the devices have been banned by several airlines...""...meaning, passengers will no longer be able to carry the devices in their carry-on or checked luggage.""Reports indicate that some hoverboards have caught on fire or have exploded due to overcharged lithium-ion batteries.""And because of this, airlines fear the gadgets could pose a potential risk while onboard an aircraft."SOURCES: Reuters, Washington Post, ABC News, NBC News, New York Daily News, http://www.reuters.com/article/us-airlines-safety-hoverboards-idUSKBN0TT2DW20151210https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/innovations/wp/2015/12/10/airlines-are-banning-hoverboards-after-fires-trigger-safety-concerns/http://abcnews.go.com/US/delta-air-lines-banned-hoverboards/story?id=35699893http://www.nbcnews.com/tech/gadgets/u-s-safety-regulators-step-probe-hoverboards-over-fire-risk-n47