      <title>Japan sends whaling fleet to slaughter 333 minke whales</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twAfter a one-year hiatus, Japan is resuming its whale hunts in the Antarctic, again maintaining the slaughter is for “scientific research.” In 2014, the International Court of Justice said Japan’s claims for the justification of its whaling practices were not rooted in scientific research and should stop. Calls of outrage from the international community to halt the expedition have not deterred Japan, and as a result, 333 minke whales will be hunted down and slaughtered between now and March 2016. The number represents a reduced kill target compared to years past, down roughly two-thirds from previous hunts.Over the next 12 years, Japan plans to capture and slaughter 4000 whales for the stated purpose of building a body of research, its attempt to prove the whale population is large enough for commercial whaling to return.An international whaling moratorium took effect across the world beginning in the 1985/1986 season, but Japan has used the “scientific research” loophole to conduct its annual slaughter ever since.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Japanese hunting ships sets sail2. Minke whales swimming below the surface3. Japanese fisherman aims harpoon at whale4. Whale is harpooned5. Boat reels in whale with ropes6. Fishermen watch as whale reeled onto boat, tail-firstVOICEOVER Japan’s claims for the justification of its whaling practices were not rooted in scientific research and should stop,But despite calls from the international community to halt the expedition, 333 minke whales will be hunted down and slaughtered between now and March of 2016. The number represents a reduced kill target compared to years past, down roughly two-thirds from previous hunts.Over the next 12 years, Japan plans to capture and slaughter 4000 whales for the stated purpose of building a body of research, Its attempt to prove the whale population is large enough for commercial whaling to return.SOURCES: *