      <title>Scientists have created malaria resistant mosquitoes</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twUniversity of California scientists have recently developed a way to create malaria resistant mosquitoes by genetic modification, which is a significant step toward eliminating malaria in humans.  Affecting half of the world’s population, malaria is caused by mosquitoes carrying the Plasmodium parasite. Sub-saharan Africa carries the highest burden of the deadly disease, accounting for 89% of malaria cases and 91% of malaria-related deaths.Scientists used a genome editing tool called “CRISPR” to alter the Anopheles stephensi mosquitoes, a common carrier of malaria. The mosquitoes’ DNA is modified by inserting a “resistance” gene, rendering them unable to carry or pass on the disease. When these genetically modified mosquitoes mate, they pass on the same malaria-resistant gene to their offspring. The new gene was inherited by almost 100% of the offspring across three generations in experiements.Scientists believe that they will be eventually able to naturally spread the edited DNA to almost all mosquitoes in a population within several generations, effectively combating malaria around the world.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. People affected by malaria 2. How malaria is spread3. CRISPR creates malaria resistant mosquitoes4+5. Gene drive and inheritance   VOICEOVER (in English): “Around 3.2 billion people, which is almost half of the world’s population, are at risk of malaria. In 2015, sub-saharan Africa alone accounts for 91% of malaria deaths.”“Malaria is a life-threatening disease caused by Plasmodium parasites. Humans are infected through bites from infected female Anopheles mosquitoes.”“Using a genome editing tool called CRISPR, scientists have successfully inserted malaria-blocking genes into mosquitoes, making them resistant to infection.” “When an altered mosquito mates with a wild mosquito, the offspring inherits both an edited copy and a normal copy of a gene. The CRISPR tool alters the normal copy to force the cell into replicating the edited version when it repairs the damage, thus resulting in two edited copies.” “Almost 100% of the mosquito offspring tested inherited the malaria-resistant gene.”       SOURCES: RT, BBC, WHO, Nature, STAT, Wiredhttps://www.rt.com/news/323361-malaria-genetically-engineered-mosquitoes/http://www.bbc.com/news/health-34898931http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs094/en/http://www.nature.com/news/gene-drive-mosquitoes-engineered-to-fight-malaria-1.18858http://www.statnews.com/2015/11/23/malaria-mosquitoes-gene-drive-crispr/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2015-11/24/malaria-resistant-mosquitoes***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
