      <title>Earth-like planet found outside solar system</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.tw A new Earth-like planet dubbed GJ 1332b has been discovered by astronomers at the Cerro-Tololo Inter-American Observatory in La Serena, Chile.  To detect it, researchers used the MEarth-South array, a group of eight 40cm robotic telescopes, and sighted it moving across the face of its M-dwarf star. Despite the planet being cooler than the sun, the closeness to the M-dwarf star makes its surface temperature reach 260 degrees Celsius. The research was published in the journal Nature. According to the Guardian, the new planet, which is about 16 percent larger than the Earth, completes an orbit every 1.6 days. Its composition is rocky and apparently similar to the one of the Earth.Although too hot to be habitable, astronomers believe GJ 1132b is cool enough to retain an atmosphere. If the planet lacks an atmosphere it may be due to the UV light and particle storms that the M-dwarf star emits, reported Gizmodo.According to the Guardian, the discovery of this planet could make it a prime target for future research missions. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. New planet GJ 1132B and its M-dwarf star2. The planet temperature3. The planet size and orbit4. The planet composition5. The planet atmosphere6. UV light and particle storms eroding the planet atmosphere on the M-dwarf starVOICEOVER (in English): "Astronomers spotted the new planet, named GJ 1132b, as it moved across the face of its M-dwarf star, which is only a fifth the size of the Sun." "Despite the star being cooler than the sun, the closeness to the M-dwarf star made its surface temperature reach 260 degrees Celsius.""The planet, which is about 16 percent larger than the Earth, completes an orbit every 1.6 days." "Its composition is rocky and apparently similar to the Earth’s.""Although too hot for life, astronomers say the planet is cool enough to retain an atmosphere." "Researchers explained if the planet lacks an atmosphere it may be due to the UV light and particle storms that the M-dwarf star emits." SOURCES: Nature, Gizmodo, The Guardian,http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v527/n7577/full/nature15762.htmlhttp://gizmodo.com/why-this-toasty-earth-sized-planet-has-astronomers-so-1741720703?trending_test_b&utm_expid=66866090-62.YkETBcIMTk2uX1oytHipyg.2&utm_referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com.tw%2Fhttp://www.theguardian.com/science/2015/nov/11/earth-like-world-gj1132b-could-be-most-important-planet-ever-found-outside-the-solar-system***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
