      <title>Pluto may be home to ice-spewing volcanoes</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twA probe has found evidence of ice volcanoes on Pluto’s surface, suggesting the dwarf planet may not be as inactive as scientists originally thought.Reuters reports that when NASA’s New Horizons spacecraft flew past Pluto on July 14, it scanned the dwarf planet’s surface and has been transmitting the data back to Earth.The latest images that were received show what appears to be two ice mountains, or cryovolcanoes, each with a depression on top, near the bottom of Sputnik Planumthe planet’s heart-shaped plain.The volcanoes, dubbed Wright Mons and Piccard Mons, are each about a hundred miles across, and 2 and 3.5 miles high respectively, reports the Smithsonian.Unlike Earth volcanoes that spew lava, the structures on Pluto would likely spew out an icy slush containing nitrogen, ammonia, and methane.The presence of mountains and icy plains suggest a geologically active surface, according to Scientific American. This indicates the presence of an internal heat source, which is speculated to be originating from radioactive elements in the core.With only 20% of New Horizons’ data downlinked to Earth, scientists will have to wait for the remaining pictures and measurements from the July encounter to confirm cryovolcanism on the dwarf planet.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. New Horizons flyby2. Pluto’s surface3. Cryovolcanoes4. Icy volcanic eruption5. Pluto’s coreVOICEOVER (in English): “When NASA’s New Horizons spacecraft flew past Pluto on July 14th, it scanned the dwarf planet’s surface and has slowly been transmitting the data back to Earth.”“The latest images show what appear to be two ice mountains, each with a depression on top, near the bottom of the planet’s heart-shaped plain.”“The volcanoes, informally called Wright Mons and Piccard Mons, are each about a hundred miles across, and 2 and 3.5 miles high, respectively. ”“Unlike Earth volcanoes that eject lava, the structures on Pluto would likely release an icy slush containing nitrogen, ammonia, and methane.”“Geological activity on the planet’s surface indicates an internal heat source, possibly coming from radioactive elements in its core.”SOURCES: BBC, Smithsonian, Scientific American, Nature, Space.com, Reutershttp://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-34771168http://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/pluto-may-have-ice-volcanoes-bottom-its-heart-180957226/?no-isthttps://www.scientificamerican.com/article/ice-volcanoes-could-be-on-pluto/http://www.nature.com/news/vibrant-pluto-stuns-scientists-1.18022http://www.space.com/31073-pluto-ice-volcano-mountains-photos.htmlhttp://www.reuters.com/article/2015/11/10/us-space-pluto-idUSKCN0SZ00120151110#FITwyeyyOhmmT6iY.97***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
