      <title>Huge drugs tunnel discovered under US-Mexico border</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twA massive state-of-the-art tunnel used to smuggle drugs between Mexico and the US was discovered by authorities during a raid, federal officials announced on Wednesday. The tunnel, connecting warehouses in Otay Mesa, near San Diego, and Tijuana in Mexico was discovered on Wednesday following simultaneous raids on both sides of the border.Officials said the tunnel was about 30 feet deep and around 2,400 feet long and featured lighting, (pause) a ventilation system, (pause) and rail tracks for transportation of the drugs.While pulleys were believed to be used by the smugglers for loading and unloading on the U.S. side of the tunnel, according to police. The bust came after a six-month operation by Homeland Security’s ICE division that saw undercover agents arrange to provide drivers for the smugglers.Sixteen people were arrested in Mexico and six were detained in the U.S., while a total of 12 tonnes of marijuana was recovered. Mexican police said that two of the suspects told them they were working for a drug cartel operating in the state of Jalisco  a reference to the Jalisco New Generation that is linked to the cartel of Joaquin ‘El Chapo’ Guzman, who escaped from a maximum security prison in July.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Location of drug tunnel near San Diego2. Cutaway showing dimensions of the tunnel (depth 30 feet, length 2,400 feet)3. Features of the tunnel (lighting, ventilation and rails)4. Pulley system used in tunnel5. Depiction of an undercover agent striking a deal with the smugglers6. Details of bust including number of arrests (22) and amount of drugs recovered (12 tonnes)VOICEOVER (in English): "The tunnel, connecting warehouses in Otay Mesa, near San Diego, and Tijuana in Mexico was discovered on Wednesday following simultaneous raids on both sides of the border.""Officials said the tunnel was about 30 feet deep and around 2,400 feet long and featured lighting, (