      <title>Wearable smart device tells you when it&#x2019;s time to go to the toilet</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twA Japanese company has invented a device that tells the user ahead of time when they will need to make a trip to the bathroom.The Japanese company, Triple W, named the white, rectangular device “Dfree”. It is secured to the user’s abdomen and predicts fecal excretion times by montoring internal organs through ultrasonic waves. The data is sent to an app on the user’s smartphone, which sends the user a notification telling them the the estimated time of their next bathroom visit.The device is aimed at those who suffer from fecal incontinence, the disabled, the elderly, and those who need more time to find the bathroom. It could also be useful for toddlers going through toilet training.Statistics show that by 2060, two out of every five Japanese will be aged 65 or older. Triple W believes the device will be a beneficial addition to Japan’s booming elder care industry.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Incontinent person, person in wheelchair, elderly person2. Device’s ultrasonic waves monitor internal organs  3. Device sends data to smartphones, users receive notifications4. Users are able to find bathrooms in time5. Possible use in toilet training6. Japan’s ageing population VOICEOVER (in English): “The device targets those who suffer from fecal incontinence, the disabled, the elderly, and those who simply need more time to find the bathroom.” “It is worn on your abdomen, and it monitors your bowel movements by emitting ultrasonic waves to your internal organs.”  “The device then collects the data and sends it to an app on your smartphone. The app will send you notifications ...” “... telling you the estimated time of your next bathroom visit.”“The device may also prove itself useful for toilet training, although its inventors have yet to find a suitable way to attach it to a toddler.”“Japan’s aging population has led to a transformation of the elder care industry. By the year 2060, two out of every five people in Japan will be aged 65 or older.”SOURCES: Reutershttp://www.reuters.com/article/2015/10/13/us-pants-toilet-idUSKCN0S71U020151013***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
