      <title>NASA&#x2019;s Kepler telescope spots possible alien megastructures surrounding huge star</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twScientists are striving to explain a recently discovered star and what its surroundings could mean for the universe.Between the Cygnus and Lyra constellations sits a peculiar star named KIC 8462852. Light patterns from this star suggest it is old. However, it is surrounded by debris like a younger star, reports Popular Mechanics.In a recent paper submitted to the  Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society, a team of scientists, led by Tabetha Boyajian, a postdoctoral fellow at Yale University, speculate the debris may be an asteroid belt or comets, the Atlantic reports. However, in another scenario, some suggest it might be extraterrestrial megastructures. According to Popular Mechanics, extraterrestrial intelligence researchers at the University of California at Berkeley are drafting a proposal to point a large radio telescope at the star and listen for signs that may indicate technological activity. Another possibility is that the data may contain some mistakes.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Location of KIC 84628522. Light patterns and surroundings of star3. Star surrounded by asteroid belt, then comets4. Extraterrestrial megastructures5. Radio telescope listening for signs of alien technological activity VOICEOVER (in English): “Between the Cygnus and Lyra constellations sits a peculiar star named KIC 8462852.”“Light patterns from this star suggest it is old. However it is surrounded by debris like a younger star.” “What this is, is what scientists are trying to figure out.”“In a recent paper, scientists speculate the debris may be an asteroid belt or comets.”“However, in another scenario, some suggest it might be extraterrestrial megastructures.”“Extraterrestrial intelligence researchers at Berkeley are reportedly seeking to point a radio telescope at the star and listen for signs that might indicate technological activity.”SOURCES: Cornell University Library, Popular Mechanics, The Atlantichttp://arxiv.org/pdf/1509.03622v1.pdfhttp://www.popularmechanics.com/space/a17769/seti-light-blips/http://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2015/10/the-most-interesting-star-in-our-galaxy/410023/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
