      <title>First ever &#x2018;in womb&#x2019; stem cell trial to begin in January</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twScientists in Sweden and the UK are conducting the first clinical trial injecting stem cells into babies still in the womb to help lessen the symptoms of Brittle Bone Disease.Brittle bone disease, also known as osteogenesis imperfecta, is caused by errors in the baby’s DNA and results in poor quality or lack of collagen in the baby’s bone structure. The disease can be fatal with babies born with multiple fractures, according to the BBC.Those babies who survive will endure up to 15 bone fractures a year, brittle teeth, impaired hearing and other growth problems. The disease affects around one in every 25,000 babies, the BBC reported.The disease is incurable at the moment. Scientists from Sweden’s Karolinska Institute and UK’s Great Ormond Street Hospital will experiment with injecting stem cells from terminated pregnancies into babies with the disease in the womb and/or after they are born in an effort to see if it may lessen the symptoms of the disease, according to the BBC.“If we could reduce the fracture frequency, strengthen bone and improve growth it would have a huge impact,” the BBC quoted Dr Cecilia Gotherstrom from the Karolinska Institute as saying. “It is the first in-­man trial and, if successful, it will pave the way for other pre­natal treatments when parents have no other option.”The trial will begin in January and will be conducted across Europe. Patients are expected to participate for two years.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Depiction of brittle bone disease caused by errors in DNA2. Depiction of a baby born with fractures3. Depiction of a baby with bone fractures, brittle teeth and hearing problems4. Depiction of injecting stem cells into baby in womb5. Depiction of injecting stem cells into baby after birth6. Depiction of symptoms lessened after injection VOICEOVER (in English): “Brittle bone disease is caused by errors in the baby’s DNA and results in poor quality or a lack of collagen in its bone structure. The disease can be fatal with babies born with multiple fractures.”“Those babies who survive will endure up to 15 bone fractures a year, brittle teeth, impaired hearing and other growth problems.”“The disease affects around one in every 25,000 babies.”“Scientists are experimenting with injecting stem cells from terminated pregnancies into babies with the disease in the womb and/or after they are born, in an effort to see if it may lessen the symptoms of the disease.”SOURCES: BBChttp://www.bbc.com/news/health-34485090***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
