      <title>UK to build &#xA3;25M Jamaican prison in prisoner transfer deal</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twUK Prime Minister David Cameron recently announced plans to sign a prisoner transfer deal that will use £25 million of British foreign aid money to build a prison in Jamaica that can fit up to 1,500 inmates.The Guardian reports that under the terms of the agreement, Jamaican prisoners in the UK with a more than four year sentence, and who still have more than 18 months left to serve by the year 2020 will be repatriated and sent to the new prison. Due to poor conditions in Jamaican prisons, inmates are unable to be deported, for fear that doing so would allow them to challenge their imprisonment under human rights law. Jamaicans make up the 3rd largest prison population of foreigners in the UK. Of the more than 600 who are currently imprisoned, roughly 69% are in for drug and violence related charges. According to the BBC, about 300 of these existing offenders are eligible to be transferred in 2020. The UK has struck similar agreements with Albania, Nigeria, Somaliland, Rwanda, and Libya. Officials have claimed the deal will save British taxpayers up to £10 million pounds in taxes per year, according to Time. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Location of new prison2. Statistics of Jamaican prisoners in the UK3. Benefits of the agreement4. Previous agreementsVOICEOVER (in English): The UK announced on Wednesday a prison transfer deal allocating 25 million pounds in foreign aid to build a prison in Jamaica big enough to fit 1,500 inmates. More than 600 Jamaican criminals make up the 3rd largest prison population of foreigners in the UK.  69% are in for drug or violence related charges. When the prison opens in 2020, those with more than 18 months left to their sentence will be sent there, reportedly saving UK taxpayers 10 million pounds a year.The UK has struck similar agreements with Albania, Nigeria, Somaliland, Rwanda, and Libya.SOURCES: BBC, The Guardian, Time, International Business Timeshttp://www.bbc