      <title>Airbus files U.S. patent for economy class &#x2018;sleeping boxes&#x2019;</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twEuropean aircraft manufacturer Airbus has filed a patent in the United States for economy-class “sleeping boxes” for long haul international flights. According to the application filed with the United States Patent and Trademark Office, the sleeping boxes, to be made of plastic or fiber-reinforced plastic, would be stacked beside and on top of each other in the rear of the aircraft. Walls are padded for safety and boxes are positioned in such a way that passengers lie perpendicular to the direction of the flight, which is reportedly safer in the event of a crash or aircraft turbulence. Each unit would be equipped with a personal TV, reclining pillows, a reading light, and video camera, which would allow flight attendants to monitor passengers. A personal service unit consisting of an emergency oxygen mask, individual air conditioning vent, loud speaker, and lamp would also be available in each box. Passengers will still need to be strapped in, but the sleeping boxes can be occupied even during taxi, takeoff, and landing. In-flight meals will be served directly to those occupying boxes, though there is an option to buy an additional seat on top of a sleeping box. Another option is for two passengers to share a sleeping box and a seat, using them alternately. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Airbus aircraft2. Sleeping boxes3. Individual amenities4. Layout of the planeVOICEOVER (in English): Aircraft manufacturer Airbus recently filed a U.S. patent for economy class ‘sleeping boxes’ on long-haul flights.The plastic boxes, stacked beside and on top of each other, are padded for safety, with no corners or edges. Each box has a personal TV, grip rails, an emergency oxygen system, loudspeaker, aircon vent, lamp, and video camera so attendants can monitor passengers.Beds are safe to occupy during taxi, takeoff, and landing since passengers lie perpendicular to the direction of the flight. SOURCES: CNN, The Daily Mail, United States Patent and Trademark Officehttp://edition.cnn.com/2015/09/29/travel/airbus-aircraft-coach-sleeping-boxes-feat/index.htmlhttp://www.dailymail.co.uk/travel/travel_news/article-3253137/Cheap-dreams-Economy-Airbus-passengers-soon-travelling-SLEEP-PODS-kitted-televisions-reclining-pillows-CCTV.htmlhttp://pdfaiw.uspto.gov/.aiw?PageNum=0&docid=20150266581&IDKey=F9C4E206F21D&HomeUrl=http%3A%2F%2Fappft.uspto.gov%2Fnetacgi%2Fnph-Parser%3FSect1%3DPTO2%2526Sect2%3DHITOFF%2526p%3D1%2526u%3D%25252Fnetahtml%25252FPTO%25252Fsearch-bool.html%2526r%3D1%2526f%3DG%2526l%3D50%2526co1%3DAND%2526d%3DPG01%2526s1%3D%252522sleeping%252Bbox%252522.TTL.%2526OS%3DTTL%2F%252522sleeping%252Bbox%252522%2526RS%3DTTL%2F%252522sleeping%252Bbox%252522***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
