      <title>First 10 womb transplants in the UK approved</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twAfter a successful womb transplant operation took place in Sweden last year, 10 British women without wombs will also be given a chance to undergo the operation in a clinical trial.According to the Womb Transplant UK team website, one in 5,000 women in the UK are born without wombs or lose their wombs to cancer. Ten British women will be selected for a womb transplant clinical trial if they are under 38, are of healthy weights and have long term partners.Dr. Richard Smith, a consultant gynaecologist at the Queen Charlotte's and Chelsea Hospital, will lead the team.Before the trial starts, embryos will be created and frozen from the women’s eggs and the sperm of their partner. The women will then undergo six-hour procedures to receive wombs from donors who are declared brain dead but still have beating hearts.''Donor retrieval is a bigger operation than transplanting the uterus into the recipient,'' Dr. Smith said in a statement. ''We don't want to subject a live donor to that operation.''The women will then be placed on immunosuppressant drugs for 12 months before the embryos can be implanted to prevent the body from rejecting the donor womb. The babies will be delivered by caesarean section to avoid placing the stress and strain of labor on their new wombs.After six months, the women can choose to have another child or have the donor wombs removed. Keeping the donor wombs would require the women to stay on immunosuppressant drugs, which have side effects, including an increased risk of cancer.If the trial is successful, the first British baby from a womb transplant mother will be born in late 2017 or 2018.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Percentage of women without wombs in the UK2. Criteria of potential recipients for donor wombs3. Embryos created and frozen before the trial4. Womb transplant procedure5. Babies will be delivered by cesarean sectionVOICEOVER (in English): “One in 5,000 women in the UK are born without wombs or lose their wombs to cancer. Ten British women will be selected for a womb transplant trial if they are under 38, are of healthy weights and have long term partners.”“Before the trial starts, embryos will be created and frozen from the women’s eggs and the sperm of their partner.”“The women will then undergo six-hour procedures to receive wombs from donors who are declared brain dead but still have beating hearts.”“The women will be placed on immunosuppressant drugs for 12 months before the embryos can be implanted.”“The babies will be delivered by caesarean section to avoid placing the stress and strain of labor on their new wombs.”SOURCES: http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2015/sep/29/10-women-receive-go-ahead-for-first-ever-womb-transplants-in-ukhttp://www.bbc.com/news/health-34397794http://wombtransplantuk.org/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
