      <title>U.S. launches massive security operations for Pope&#x2019;s visit</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twAuthorities have launched one of the largest security operations in U.S. history in preparation for Pope Francis’s visit.The pope is arrives in Washington, DC on Tuesday. He will depart for New York on Thursday, and travel to Philadelphia on Saturday, where he will hold an open-air Mass, expected to be attended by more than a million people.The Secret Service is in charge of coordinating the massive security operation along with the FBI, Capitol Police, Coast Guard, Pentagon, Federal Emergency Management Agency and local police. Up to 90 staff members from 50 agencies will monitor video, radio and other communications around the clock at the Multi-Agency Communications Center, the Washington Post reported. Senior members of the Secret Service travelled to the Vatican to meet with the Pope’s security force, the Swiss Guard, ahead of the visit. The Guards also made multiple trips to Washington for security planning, KUTV reported.Vatican officials instructed Secret Service agents to not to manhandle the Pope in rope lines, a common tactic used to protect U.S. presidents. U.S. lawmakers are told to not to shake hands or touch the Pope as he walks through the House chamber, according to the Washington Post.Security measures will be extremely intense in Philadelphia, where authorities have set up three security perimeters. Along the first perimeter, incoming traffic will be blocked from the Delaware River to 38th Street and from South Street north to Girard Avenue. The second perimeter includes the Benjamin Franklin Parkway and Independence Mall areas, where no traffic, except designated vehicles, will be allowed. The third perimeter will include security checkpoints and fencing. Sections of major highways will also be closed, PennLive.com reported.Some security experts have questioned whether the level of security would bring about inconveniences that would be too extreme or even counterproductive.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Pope’s itinerary2. Security departments involved in the operations3. Secret Service agents travelling to the Vatican to meet with the Swiss Guards4. Swiss Guards travelling to Washington5. Secret Service agents not to manhold the pope in rope lines 6. Lawmakers told not to touch the pope7. Agents monitoring at a center around the clock8. Security zones in Philadelphia9. Prohibited itemsVOICEOVER (in English): “The pope arrives in Washington, DC on Tuesday. He will depart for New York on Thursday, and to Philadelphia on Saturday, where he will hold an open-air Mass, expected to be attended by more than a million people.”“The Secret Service is in charge of coordinating the massive security operation along with the FBI, Capitol Police, Coast Guard, Pentagon, Federal Emergency Management Agency and local police.”“Senior members of the Secret Service travelled to the Vatican to meet with the Pope’s security force, the Swiss Guard, ahead of the visit. The Guards also made multiple trips to Washington for security planning.”“Vatican officials instructed Secret Service agents not to manhandle the Pope in rope lines, a common tactic used to protect U.S. presidents.”“U.S. lawmakers are told not to shake hands or touch the Pope as he walks through the House chamber.”“Up to 90 staff members from 50 agencies will monitor video, radio and other communications around the clock at the Multi-Agency Communications Center.”“Security measures will be extremely intense in Philadelphia, where authorities have set up three security perimeters. Along the first perimeter, incoming traffic will be blocked from the Delaware River to 38th Street and from South Street north to Girard Avenue. The second perimeter includes the Benjamin Franklin Parkway and Independence Mall areas, where no traffic, except designated vehicles, will be allowed. The third perimeter will include security checkpoints and fencing. Sections of major highways will also be closed.”“All attendees of