      <title>China appears to be building third airstrip in Spratly Islands</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twChina may be building a third airstrip in the disputed Spratly Islands in the South China Sea, according to a Washington-based think tank.Satellite images taken on September 8 show that China had reclaimed a piece of land with a retaining wall about 3,000 meters long on Mischief Reef, which is suspected to be an airstrip under construction, CNN reported. China is already building airstrips on Fiery Cross Reef and Subi Reef.“If it does turn out to be a runway, China will have three airstrips that can carry any plane the PLA [People’s Liberation Army] has to offer,” Greg Poling, the director of Washington-based Center for Strategic and International Studies’ Asia Maritime Transparency Initiative, told CNN.The United States says China has reclaimed some 2,000 acres, or the equivalent of around 1,500 football fields, in the Spratly Islands over the past 18 months, according to CNN.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Airstrip being built on Mischief Reef2. Chinese airstrips on Mischief, Fiery Cross and Subi reefs3. Amount of land reclaimed by China in the South China Sea over the past 18 monthsVOICEOVER (in English): “China had reclaimed a piece of land with a retaining wall about 3,000 meters long on Mischief Reef, which is suspected to be an airstrip under construction.”“If so, it would be the third Chinese airstrip under construction in the Spratly Islands. China is already building airstrips on Fiery Cross Reef and Subi Reef.”“The United States says China has reclaimed some 2,000 acres, or the equivalent of around 1,500 football fields, in the Spratly Islands over the past 18 months.”SOURCES: CNN, Asia Maritime Transparency Initiative, Reutershttp://edition.cnn.com/2015/09/15/asia/china-south-china-sea-airstrip/index.htmlhttp://amti.csis.org/mischief-reef-tracker/http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/09/15/us-china-southchinasea-airstrips-idUSKCN0RE28220150915***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.c