      <title>China plans to send the first spacecraft to land on moon&#x2019;s dark side</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twChina, which landed a probe on the moon in 2013, now plans to be the first country to land a probe on the moon’s far side by 2020.The far side of the moon, most of which is never visible from Earth, has been observed by various probes, but no one has ever attempted a landing.The Chinese mission will be conducted by the Chang’e-4 spacecraft. The Chang’e-4 is able to handle a larger payload than China’s previous lunar mission, the Chang’e 3, Zou Yongliao of the Chinese Academy of Sciences' moon exploration department told China’s state-run CCTV.The Chang’e-4 will orbit the moon and look for the right spot to deploy its rover. After making a soft landing, the lunar rover will dig and collect rock samples from up to 2 meters below the surface.According to CNN, some security experts fear that China is looking to lay claim to the moon’s resources, which include water and Helium 3, a clean-burning fuel that could offer an alternative to nuclear power.The U.S. is also looking at the moon for resources, and NASA is working with private companies to find ways to mine the Earth’s satellite, CNBC News reported. Chang’e-3 landed on the moon in 2013 and released a rover called Jade Rabbit, which is still on the moon, making China the third country, after the U.S. and the former Soviet Union, to land a probe on lunar soil. Now other nations in the Asia are trying to match China’s achievements. Japan has announced it will land an unmanned rover on the moon by 2018.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. The moon’s dark side2. Electromagnetic environment of the moon’s dark side and low-frequency radio study 3. Chang'e-4 spacecraft has a larger payload than the Chang’e 34. Chang'e-4 orbiting the moon5. Chang'e-4’s probe landing and conducting geological measurements6. The moon is a source of considerable resources VOICEOVER (in English): “Called the ‘dark side,’ most of the far side of the moon is never visible from Earth because the moon’s orbital and rotational periods are nearly synchronized.”“An official at the Chinese Academy of Sciences' moon exploration department told China’s state-run CCTV that the moon’s dark side has a ‘clean electromagnetic environment, which is an ideal field for low-frequency radio study.’”“The Chinese mission will be conducted by the Chang’e-4 spacecraft, which is able to handle a larger payload than China’s previous lunar mission, the Chang’e 3.”“The Chang’e-4 will orbit the moon and look for the right spot to deploy its rover.”“After making a soft landing, the lunar rover will dig and collect rock samples from up to 2 meters below the surface.”“Some security experts fear that China is looking to lay claim to the moon’s resources, which include water and Helium 3, a clean-burning fuel that could offer an alternative to nuclear power.”SOURCES:  CNN, China Times, Beijing Review, Al Jazeera, CNBC, China Dailyhttp://edition.cnn.com/2015/09/09/asia/china-moon-exploration-dark-side/http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20150910000071&cid=1104http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2015/09/china-spacecraft-aims-reach-dark-side-moon-150909064300824.htmlhttp://www.cnbc.com/2015/03/10/billionaire-teams-up-with-nasa-to-mine-the-moon.htmlhttp://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2015-09/09/content_21823406.htm***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
