      <title>Massive neolithic ritual site with 90 megaliths discovered near Stonehenge</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twIn what may prove to be the largest Neolithic site ever discovered in Britain, and possibly in Europe, archeologists have found a row of 90 megaliths near Stonehenge.The 4,500-year-old stones, which are up to 15 feet tall and five feet wide were found, thanks to the use of sophisticated ground-penetrating radar equipment, buried under a thick grassy bank. They were lying horizontally, three feet underground. It is conceivable that they originally stood vertically in the ground, like other standing stones in Britain, and that the stone line marked a ritual procession route in a gigantic ceremonial complex.Archaeologists believe the megaliths were ultimately deliberately pushed over and buried. Durrington Walls, the site where the stones were found, is 12 times the area of Stonehenge and was arranged with the same summer solstice alignment, the Telegraph reported. Another nearby wooden structure named Woodhenge was thought to represent the land of the living, while Stonehenge represented the realm of the dead.The research on this new discovery, which opens a new chapter of the Stonehenge story, will be presented at the British Science Festival in Bradford this week.Paul Garwood, an archaeologist and lead historian on the project at the University of Birmingham, was quoted by the Guardian as saying that the new discovery has changed fundamentally how researchers understand Stonehenge and the world around it.“Everything written previously about the Stonehenge landscape and the ancient monuments within it will need to be rewritten,” Garwood said.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. The stone monument made of a row of 90 megaliths2. The location of the stone monument near Stonehenge3. The stones’ height, width and material4. The stones found using ground-penetrating radar equipment5. The stones lying horizontally three feet underground 6. The stones standing vertically7. The stone line used as a ritual procession route8. The megaliths being pushed over deliberately and a bank being built on top of them9. The Durrington Walls monument going from a C-shaped structure to a roughly circular enclosure10. The Durrington Walls site diameter, the width of its ditch and the height of its bank11. Durrington Walls stone monument built on the same summer solstice alignment as Stonehenge 12. Woodhenge representing the land of the living13. Stonehenge representing the realm of the deadVOICEOVER (in English): [TITLE CUT]“The massive stone monument comprised of a row of 90 megalithic stones was found buried under a thick grassy bank beneath the prehistoric super-henge of Durrington Walls, less than two miles from Stonehenge in Wiltshire.”“The line of 4,500-year-old megaliths, which are up to 15 feet tall and 5 feet wide and are believed to be sarsen stones,was found with the use of sophisticated ground-penetrating radar equipment.”“They were lying horizontally, 3 feet underground. “It is conceivable that they originally stood vertically in the ground like other standing stones in Britain, “and that the stone line marked a ritual procession route in a gigantic ceremonial complex.”“Archaeologists believe the megaliths were eventually pushed over deliberately and a bank built on top.”“From a C-shaped monument facing the river Avon, the entire structure was later shaped into a roughly circular enclosure, now known as Durrington Walls.”　“The site measures around 1,640 feet in diameter and is surrounded by a ditch up to 54 feet wide and a bank of more than 3 feet high.” “It is built on the same summer solstice alignment as Stonehenge.”“A nearby wooden structure, called Woodhenge, which archeologists are still not sure had or did not have a roof, was thought to represent the land of the living ... while Stonehenge represented the realm of the dead.”SOURCES: The Guardian, BBC, Visit Stonehenge, Sky News, The Telegraph, http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/sep/07/stone]]></description>
