      <title>Nazi gold train reportedly found in Poland</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twAfter 70 years of unsuccessful attempts by various treasure hunters, two men claim to have found a legendary Nazi gold train in Poland.BBC News reports that the two men, a Pole and a German, filed a “finder's claim” for an armored train carrying precious metals. Under Polish law, they are entitled to 10 percent of their find.According to Polish legend, the Germans packed an armored train with gold, jewels and guns and sent it southwest in 1945 as the Soviets were closing in, the Telegraph writes.The train is rumored to have disappeared near Ksiaz castle, in the mountainous Lower Silesia region. It is believed the train entered a tunnel, never to emerge.BBC News reports that the train was filled with 300 tons of gold. The duo claim to have found it near Walbrzych, only 3 km from Ksiaz Castle.The Nazis had an extensive history of looting. They are known for having stolen famous artwork and confiscated their prisoners’ money, jewelry and precious belongings.Some sceptics believe there is no evidence to support the existence of such a train, but some historians point out that the Nazis dug miles of tunnels in southwestern Poland.“Lawyers, the army, the police and the fire brigade were dealing with this,” Marika Tokarska, a Walbrzych district council official, told Reuters.Tokarska added that she did not know anything about either the location or the contents of the missing train.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Two men entitled to 10 percent of their find2. Nazi soldiers loading a train with gold, jewels and guns3. Train enters a tunnel, entrance is blocked4. Possible location of the missing train5. Nazi soldiers looting artwork and jewels6. Network of tunnels in southwestern PolandVOICEOVER (in English): “The two men, a Pole and a German, filed a ‘finder's claim’ for an armored train carrying precious metals. Under Polish law, they are entitled to 10 percent of their find.”“According to Polish legend, the Germans packed an armored train with gold, jewels and guns and sent it southwest in 1945 as the Soviets were closing in.”“The train is rumored to have disappeared near Ksiaz castle, in the mountainous Lower Silesia region. It is believed the train entered a tunnel, never to emerge.”“It is said the train was filled with 300 tons of gold. The duo claim to have found it near Walbrzych, only 3 km from Ksiaz Castle.”“The Nazis had an extensive history of looting. They are known for having stolen famous artwork and confiscated their prisoners’ money, jewelry and precious belongings.”“Some sceptics believe there is no evidence to support the existence of such a train, but historians point out that the Nazis dug miles of tunnels in southwestern Poland.”SOURCES: BBC, Daily Mail, Telegraph, Expresshttp://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-33994483http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3203511/Poland-looking-report-Nazi-treasure-train-found.htmlhttp://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/germany/11812174/Has-a-lost-Nazi-ghost-train-carrying-gold-finally-been-found-Two-treasure-hunters-think-so.htmlhttp://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/germany/9880969/Hunt-begins-for-legendary-1billion-in-Nazi-gold.htmlhttp://www.express.co.uk/news/world/599442/Nazi-gold-train-Walbrzych-Poland***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
