      <title>Scientists predict this year&#x2019;s El Nino will be strongest on record</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twScientists at NOAA’s Climate Prediction Center released a forecast on Thursday predicting that this year’s El Nino event could be one of the strongest ever.Conditions are ripe for the most powerful El Nino ever recorded as sea surface temperatures in the Pacific Ocean are as much as 3.5 degrees fahrenheit above average. NOAA’s noted much of the ocean conditions they are seeing now are comparable to the ones they saw before the disastrous El Nino winters of 1982 -83 and 1997-98. During these periods, El Nino wreaked havoc across the western United States and in parts of South Asia, South America and East Africa. Weakened winds that usually blow warm waters in the eastern Pacific to Indonesia and Australia, as well as the unusually warm atmosphere that characterizes El Nino will shift a subtropical jet stream that usually travels through Latin America toward California and the southern states, causing the area to experience extreme rainfall. After the 1997 El Nino event, southern California got double its annual amount of rainfall while Los Angeles received a year’s worth of rainfall in one month alone.CNN reports that warmer waters will drive away coldwater fish in the eastern Pacific, a key component of many economies along the American coast.While increased rainfall in California may help counter the area’s four-year drought, scientists caution against thinking that the El Nino event will solve the state’s water issues. California needs 2.5 times its average rainfall to patch its current water deficit. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Warming waters in the eastern Pacific Ocean2. Atmospheric heating3. Jet stream sending warmer airs and storms to California coast4. Warmer surface waters drive coldwater fish away5. Increased rainfall from El Nino won’t cure California’s droughtVOICEOVER (in English): “Scientists at NOAA’s Climate Prediction Center released a forecast on Thursday predicting that this year’s El Nino could be one of the strongest ever.”“Conditions are ripe for the most powerful El Nino ever recorded as sea surface temperatures in the Pacific Ocean are as much as 3.5 degrees fahrenheit above average.”“Weakened winds that usually blow warm waters in the eastern Pacific to Indonesia and Australia, as well as the unusually warm atmosphere that characterizes El Nino...”“...will shift a subtropical jet stream toward California and the southern states, causing the area to experience extreme rainfall.”“CNN reports that warmer waters will drive away coldwater fish in the eastern Pacific, a key component of many economies along the American coast.”“While increased rainfall in California may help counter the area’s four-year drought, the state needs 2.5 times its average rainfall to patch its water deficit.”SOURCES: USA Today, Time, San Francisco Chronicle, CNN, Los Angeles Timeshttp://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2015/08/13/godzilla-el-nino/31647757/http://time.com/3996227/el-nino-forecast/http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/El-Ni-o-getting-bigger-and-bigger-6442359.phphttp://edition.cnn.com/2015/08/13/weather/el-nino-2015/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-el-nino-20150813-htmlstory.html***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
