      <title>Japan reopens first nuclear reactor since Fukushima</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twJapan’s Kyushu Electric Power restarted one of the two reactors at its Sendai nuclear power plant in Kagoshima on Tuesday. The reopening of the Sendai reactor will mark the first time Japan has generated nuclear power after the start of its post-Fukushima ‘zero nuclear’ period.During the nuclear plant’s hiatus, Japan desperately relied on thermal energy, however, the country has struggled with meeting the soaring costs of purchasing oil, gas and other fuels. Kyushu Electric Power announced that the reason they are reopening the reactor is the country’s lack of electricity. On August 11, the reactor successfully sustained a nuclear chain reaction and will soon begin to generate electricity.In hopes of strengthening the nuclear plant’s safety measures, 11 electric companies will invest 3 trillion JPY towards the facility’s safety systems. Residents living near nuclear power plants are still anxious about their safety though, and the possibility of insufficient emergency measures in the event of a nuclear accident.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Kyushu Electric Power restarts the Sendai reactor2. Nuclear power is necessary for lowering electricity prices3. Lack of electricity supply is the reason for restarting the reactor4. The reactor achieves a sustained nuclear chain reaction5. Eleven electric companies invest to strengthen the facility’s safety measuresVOICEOVER (in English): In September 2013, Kansai Electric Power's Oi plant in Fukui Prefecture went offline for a routine safety check. The reopening of the Sendai reactor will mark the first time Japan has generated nuclear power after the start of its post-Fukushima ‘zero nuclear’ period.During Japan’s nuclear power hiatus, Japan has relied on thermal energy. However, the country now struggles with meeting the soaring costs of purchasing oil, gas and other fuels.Kyushu Electric Power announced that the reason they are reopening the reactor is the country’s lack of electricity. On August 11, the reactor successfully sustained a nuclear chain reaction and will soon begin to generate electricity.In hopes of strengthening the nuclear plant’s safety measures, 11 electric companies will invest 3 trillion yen towards the facility’s safety systems.SOURCES: Kyodo News, The Japan Times, The Asahi Shimbun, The Mainichi, Jiji Press, NHK Worldhttp://english.kyodonews.jp/news/2015/08/368599.htmlhttp://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/08/11/national/nuclear-restart-highlights-government-dilemma-lack-waste-disposal-sites/#.VcqOivntlBchttp://ajw.asahi.com/article/behind_news/social_affairs/AJ201508110066http://mainichi.jp/english/english/newsselect/news/20150811p2a00m0na017000c.htmlhttp://jen.jiji.com/jc/eng?g=eco&k=2015081200003http://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/english/news/20150812_03.html***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
