      <title>Millions of plastic shade balls will protect the water in LA&#x2019;s reservoirs</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twMillions of plastic shade balls were poured into the Los Angeles Reservoir on Monday to help protect water quality and prevent evaporation.Hollow and weighted down with water, the balls will remain on the water’s surface and protect the water from dust, rain, birds and reduce algae growth. The balls will also block the water surface from the sun, preventing bromide and chlorine in the water from reacting and forming bromate, a known carcinogen. Less than $35 million was used to produce the shade balls, an amount much smaller than the estimated $300 million cost of covering the 175-acre facility."This is a blend of how engineering really meets common sense. We saved a lot of money, we did all the right things," said Los Angeles Department of Water and Power General Manager Marcie Edwards at a press conference.Los Angeles is the first city in the United States to use shade balls. Ninety-six million shade balls have been poured into several reservoirs in LA. According to ABC 7 News, the balls will prevent an estimated 300 million gallons of water from evaporating into the air each year.The balls can last 10 years inside the reservoirs before they are recycled and replaced. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Showcasing the shade balls2. Balls will protect water against dust, rain, birds and algae growth3. Balls will prevent bromate formation4. Other locations that use shade balls5. How much water will be conservedVOICEOVER (in English): “The shade balls have a four-inch-long diameter and are hollow, made from plastic, and are coated in a chemical that blocks out ultraviolet light.”“The balls, which are weighted with water, protect the reservoir against dust, rain, birds and reduce algae growth.”“The balls will also block the water surface from sunlight, thereby preventing bromide and chlorine in the water from reacting to form bromate, a carcinogen.”“Ninety-six million shade balls have been poured into several reservoirs in LA and will prevent an estimated 300 million gallons of water from evaporating into the air each year.”SOURCES: http://abc7.com/news/millions-of-shade-balls-protecting-los-angeles-reservoir/920083/http://www.vox.com/2015/8/11/9130563/shade-balls-are-californias-most-mesmerizing-water-saving-trick***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
