      <title>Lexus showed its hoverboard in action in Barcelona, Spain</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twLexus has created a working hoverboard that uses liquid nitrogen and magnets to glide above a magnetic track. The hoverboard was formally unveiled on Tuesday in a 2-minute video posted on YouTube.Lexus engineers used a copper oxide superconductor as the main “engine” of the hoverboard. Liquid nitrogen is poured onto the copper oxide to make it superconductive. When the chilled superconductor is placed above the magnetic track, a phenomena called “flux pinning” traps the superconductor in space above the magnet, maintaining the hover height of the board.Lexus and its German engineering partner Evico installed hundreds of magnets at a skate park in Barcelona to convert it into a hoverboard track where Lexus debuted the hoverboard.The hoverboard was developed by engineers at Lexus’ Tokyo division and is the fourth project in the company’s “Amazing Motion” publicity campaign.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. The idea of hoverboard’s mechanics is shown.2. Liquid nitrogen is poured in and the superconductor cools down.3. The board is made of bamboo and it can carry 200 kg.4. Cryostats keep the superconductor cool until it needs nitrogen again.5. A man skates using the hoverboard on a narrow magnetic pathway.6. The hoverpark has magnetic pathways built below it.VOICEOVER (in English): [TITLE CUT]LEXUS SHOWS OFF MAGICFUNCTIONING HOVERBOARD “Lexus formally unveiled a functioning hoverboard on Tuesday in a 2-minute video posted on YouTube.”“The hoverboard uses electromagnets to lift it off a surface, allowing for near frictionless movement.”“Inside the hoverboard is a copper oxide superconductor, which is cooled to below 200 degrees Celsius using liquid nitrogen to make it superconductive.”“The board itself is made of bamboo and can carry weights of up to 200 kg.”“Cryostats on both ends of the board allow for constant cooling of the superconductor. The board can be refilled with liquid nitrogen if needed.”“The board achieves levitation on pathways lined with hundreds of magnets. The board and the pathway interact to create ‘flux pinning,’ a trapped magnetic field.”“The hoverboard can only glide on these magnetic pathways and not on ordinary surfaces.”“The hoverboard was developed by engineers at Lexus’ Tokyo division and is the fourth project in the company’s ‘Amazing Motion’ publicity campaign.”SOURCES: Lexus, Inside Sciencehttp://www.lexus-int.com/amazinginmotion/slide/http://www.insidescience.org/blog/2015/06/26/how-lexus-hoverboard-gets-ground***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
