      <title>New Japan technology helps determine what missing fugitives from long ago look like today</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twThe National Research Institute of Police Science in Japan has developed a new program that uses anatomical data to simulate what a person would look like after aging in order to determine what fugitive suspects who went missing years ago might look like today.The National Police Agency believes the technology will help them track down fugitives who went missing long ago more efficiently, as previous methods do not render images that look like what the suspects currently look like.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. People looking at a wanted poster, but it does not look like what the suspect currently looks like2. Previous methods only added wrinkles or other imperfections to images3. New technology helps police determine what 876 missing people from 10 years ago might look like today4. The suspect responsible for a sarin gas attack in 1995 looked nothing like his poster when he was arrested in 2012VOICEOVER (in English): “The National Research Institute of Police Science in Japan has developed a program to more accurately simulate what a person would look like after aging. This will help police more efficiently pursue fugitive suspects or find long-lost missing persons.”“Japanese police renderings of long-lost fugitives or missing person’s faces previously only added wrinkles, but these images did not accurately depict what a person looks like after aging.”“New technology has enabled police to render the faces of 876 missing people with added anatomical data to more accurately depict what they look like 10 years later.”“The new technology comes after the 2012 arrest of the suspect charged with a sarin gas attack in Japan’s subway system in 1995. At the time of his arrest, the suspect looked nothing like the image of his face police had distributed.”SOURCES: Nikkeihttp://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXLASDG02H4R_S5A800C1000000/Sankeihttp://www.sanspo.com/geino/news/20150803/sot15080305010004-n1.htmlReutershttp://jp.reuters.com/article/2015/08/02/idJP2015080201001236Kyodohttp://www.47news.jp/CN/201508/CN2015080201001208.html***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
