      <title>Amazon proposes delivery drone traffic control at NASA conference</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twU.S. online retailer Amazon on Tuesday called for new air traffic rules for commercial drone flights. The proposal was unveiled by Gur Kimchi, Amazon’s vice president in charge of the company’s fledgling drone delivery program, at a NASA-sponsored conference at the agency’s Ames Research Center in Mountain View, California. The Ames Research Center is home to a NASA team charged with the development of an air-traffic system called Unmanned Aerial System Traffic Management. Amazon proposed that airspace be segregated between unmanned and manned aircraft. Unmanned aircraft, or drones, making local deliveries and moving slowly would be restricted to airspace under 200 feet. Airspace between 200 and 400 feet would be reserved for high-speed drones traveling long distances.  No aircraft would be able to fly between 400 and 500 feet, and only manned aircraft could fly above 500 feet. High-speed delivery drones would file a flight plan with a central computer and be required to maintain internet connectivity while in flight. High-speed delivery drones would also download a list of obstacles and airspace to avoid from the central computer. All high-speed delivery drones would have sensors to detect manned aircraft, birds and other unexpected obstacles that might enter the drone’s path of travel. The drone would give way to manned aircraft and automatically avoid other threats.Amazon’s proposal envisions a future with thousands of drones sharing the sky in a manner similar to automobile traffic on a highway. Amazon hopes its proposal will speed the FAA’s acceptance of the company's drone delivery model. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Cross section of airspace reserved for slow drones, fast drones and manned aircraft2. Drones have flight plan to avoid obstacles3. Drones can detect and avoid aircraft4. Drones can detect and avoid birds5. Drones traveling along “highways” in the air6. Drone delivers package to private residenceVOICEOVER (in English): [TITLE CUT]AMAZON PROPOSES NEW AIR RULESFOR HIGH-SPEED DRONE DELIVERIES read this VO for title cut:[PHOTO] AMAZON.COM 1,2,3On Tuesday, Amazon proposed new air traffic rules for controlling delivery drones at a NASA sponsored conference in Mountain View, California. [CUT 1]10sec - altitude levelsVO: Amazon proposed that airspace under 200 feet be reserved for slow-moving drones, and airspace between 200 and 400 feet for high-speed drones. No aircraft would be able to fly between 400 and 500 feet, and only manned aircraft could fly above 500 feet. [CUT 2]7sec - avoiding obstaclesVO: High-speed delivery drones will file a flight plan with a central computer and download a list of obstacles and airspace to avoid. [CUT 3]4sec - avoiding helicopter-VO: High-speed drones can detect aircraft in their path and will always give way. [CUT 4]4sec - avoiding birds-VO: They can also detect smaller, unexpected obstacles, like birds. [CUT 5]4sec - descending from traffic laneVO: The proposed regulations envision a future with thousands of drones sharing the sky,[CUT 6]5sec - receiving packageVO: and Amazon hopes its proposal will speed the FAA’s acceptance of its drone delivery model. [PHOTO]SOURCES: Bloomberg, Amazon Prime Air, IEEE Spectrum, http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-07-28/amazon-envisions-distinct-drone-zones-for-future-delivery-fleethttp://www.amazon.com/b?node=8037720011http://spectrum.ieee.org/view-from-the-valley/robotics/aerial-robots/drone-control-heres-how-amazon-thinks-drones-should-fit-into-us-airspacehttp://spectrum.ieee.org/view-from-the-valley/robotics/aerial-robots/package-delivery-by-drone***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
