      <title>Flaw in Android software may allow hackers access to phones with just a single text</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twSecurity firm Zimperium told NPR that a weakness in an Android-based software may allow hackers to affect 95 percent of Android phones with just a single text. According to Zimperium, hackers can take advantage of flaws in Android software Stagefright, a multimedia processing tool in Android devices. However, the firm discovered the bug in their lab and don’t believe hackers are using it just yet.Malware can be incorporated into a video file and sent to an individual’s Android phone. If the message is received via Google Hangouts, Stagefright will immediately process the video and release the malware whether the file was actually opened or not. Though, if an individual is using the standard messaging software they would need to open the text before the video is processed. The malware can take complete control over the phone and allow hackers to gain access to all of the information stored inside, including taking over the phone’s camera and microphone.Google has developed patches that can protect Android users and has reportedly sent them out, but it’s ultimately up to phone carriers and phone makers to push the updates through to individual phones. Old devices often stop receiving updates altogether and are therefore left vulnerable to hacks and new issues that crop up.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Percentage of Androids that may be affected2. Malware takes advantage of Android software Stagefright3. How the malware may be released on the phones4. Malware will take complete control over the phone5. Challenges Google faces in responding to the threatVOICEOVER: “Security firm Zimperium told NPR that a weakness in an Android-based software may allow a malware to affect 95 percent of Android phones.”“According to Zimperium, hackers can take advantage of flaws in Android software Stagefright, a multimedia processing tool.”“Malware can be incorporated into a video file and sent to an individual’s Android phone. If the message is received via Google Hangouts, Stagefright will immediately process the video and release the malware whether the file was actually opened or not.”“The malware can take complete control over the phone and allow hackers to gain access to all of the information stored inside.”“Google has developed patches that can protect Android users and has reportedly sent them out, but it’s ultimately up to phone carriers and phone makers to push the updates through to individual phones.”SOURCES: CNET, NPR, PCWorldhttp://www.cnet.com/news/researcher-finds-mother-of-all-android-vulnerabilities/http://www.npr.org/sections/alltechconsidered/2015/07/27/426613020/major-flaw-in-android-phones-would-let-hackers-in-with-just-a-texthttp://www.pcworld.com/article/2953052/security/most-android-phones-can-be-hacked-with-a-simple-mms-message-or-multimedia-file.html***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
