      <title>Japan&#x2019;s experimental plane creates quieter sonic boom</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twThe Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency (JAXA) has successfully tested an experimental supersonic aircraft that emits a quieter sonic boom.The plane’s design reduces shockwaves typically created during supersonic flight, resulting in a quieter sonic boom, according to Popular Mechanics.In an experiment, the plane was dropped from a balloon at an altitude of 30 kilometers and reached supersonic speeds during free fall. The sonic boom data was collected via several aerial microphones attached to a blimp.However, according to Popular Mechanics, it is unclear how the Japanese plane accomplishes this.Sonic booms are created when shockwaves produced by an aircraft that has reached supersonic flight merge into a single sound.The plane, flight tested by Japanese space agency JAXA, and reportedly built to specifications conceived by Sweden’s Esrange Space Center, represents an attempt to rectify some of the issues faced by the world’s first supersonic commercial jet, the Concorde, which had its European routes cancelled due to noise levels.JAXA expects to release detailed data from the experiment in the near future. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Previous supersonic plane causing a lot of noise2. Concorde aircrafts no longer used starting in 20033. JAXA pairs up with Swedish company for experimental plane4. Depiction of experimentVOICEOVER (in English): “The plane’s design reduces shockwaves typically created during supersonic flight, resulting in a quieter sonic boom, according to Popular Mechanics.”“The aircraft represents an attempt to rectify some of the issues faced by the world’s first supersonic commercial jet, the Concorde, which had its European routes cancelled due to noise levels.”“The plane, flight tested by Japanese space agency JAXA, was reportedly built to specifications conceived by Sweden’s Esrange Space Center.”“In an experiment, the plane was dropped from a balloon at an altitude of 30 kilometers and reached supersonic speeds during free fall. The sonic boom data was collected via several aerial microphones attached to a blimp.”SOURCES: Japan Aerospace Exploration Agencyhttp://www.jaxa.jp/press/2015/07/20150727_dsend2_j.htmlhttp://www.jaxa.jp/article/special/aviation/oonuki01_j.htmlhttp://global.jaxa.jp/press/2015/07/20150727_dsend2.htmlKyodohttp://www.47news.jp/CN/201507/CN2015072701001846.htmlYomiurihttp://www.yomiuri.co.jp/science/20150727-OYT1T50094.htmlSankeihttp://www.sankei.com/life/news/150727/lif1507270038-n1.htmlNikkeihttp://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXLASDG27HBR_X20C15A7CR8000/Mynavihttp://news.mynavi.jp/news/2015/07/27/371/Popular Mechanicshttp://www.popularmechanics.com/flight/news/a16619/jaxa-experiemental-plane-has-quieter-sonic-booms/Military Technologieshttp://www.military-technologies.net/2015/07/27/release-results-for-the-second-phase-of-the-drop-test-for-the-simplified-evaluation-of-non-symmetrically-distributed-sonic-boom-project-d-send2/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
