      <title>Honda&#x2019;s robotic walking assistant aids people learning to walk again</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twHonda has announced that in November it will begin to lease a robotic device designed to help people learning to walk again after sustaining an injury.According to the company, the Honda Walking Assist Device has been undergoing development since 1999 and has already been trialled at roughly 50 hospitals and other facilities in Japan since 2013.The technology was carried out as part of the research and development of ASIMO, Honda’s advanced humanoid robot. It is based on the inverted pendulum model, which is a theory of bipedal walking. Two motors on the device helps people lift their legs at the thigh as the leg it moves forward and backward. This lengthens the user’s stride, allowing them to walk further and faster.Honda says that the motors and control system have also been designed to be ultra-light weight, while the belt design and size-adjustable frames make it more accessible to put on and take off for all patients.The technology comes with a variety of training modes, including follow mode, where the device follows the patients' walking patterns, and symmetric mode, where the device adjusts the user’s walking pattern to help them achieve more symmetry in their motions when they bend and extend both legs. The step mode alters the user’s steps repeatedly to enable them to shift their weight from heel to sole and sole to toe more smoothly.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. An elderly person having trouble walking2. Robotic walking assistant measuring the walking patterns of a user3. Weight and lifespan of the robotic walking assistant4. Robot set to be available to hospitals starting in November 20155. Elderly people walking with ease with the help of robotic walking assistantVOICEOVER (in English): Automobile manufacturer Honda has developed a robotic walking assistant device to help rehabilitate patients learning to walk again. The device can also aid the elderly and those with walking disabilities.When the device is attached around a person’s pelvis and thighs, a sensor measures the walking patterns of each user and submits data displayed visually on a tablet.The robotic walking assistant device weighs around 2.7 kilograms, and has a battery life that lasts about 60 minutes.In November 2015, the robotic walking assistant device will be available to medical institutions in Japan.The device is expected to improve users’ motor skills and increase the distance they can walk.SOURCES: http://www.honda.co.jp/news/2015/p150721.html?from=topbannerhttp://car.watch.impress.co.jp/docs/news/20150722_712728.htmlhttp://www.sankei.com/economy/news/150721/ecn1507210042-n1.htmlhttp://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXLASDZ21HH1_R20C15A7TI5000/http://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20150721/k10010161361000.htmlhttp://japan.cnet.com/news/service/35067649/http://eandt.theiet.org/news/2015/jul/honda-walking.cfm***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
