      <title>Giant earthquake predicted to hit Pacific Northwest of the United States</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twAccording to peer review studies recently highlighted in a New Yorker article, a giant earthquake is expected to hit the Pacific Northwest along the Cascadia subduction zone and strike an area that’s currently ill-prepared to handle its consequences.The Cascadia subduction zone is a fault line that runs from Cape Mendocino in northern California to Vancouver Island, Canada. It sits next to Juan de Fuca, an oceanic plate that continuously pushes against the North American continental plate.When the Juan de Fuca plate slides under the North American plate, it will cause an earthquake of a magnitude between 8.7 and 9.2 on the Richter scale, which dwarfs any earthquake unleashed by the San Andreas fault line. When the oceanic plate slides under Canada and the U.S., the entire coastal area will sink at least six feet in less than five minutes.Experts predict that northern California and Oregon will receive the greatest impact from the massive quake. They also predict that the massive earthquake and the tsunami that follows it, will displace millions, obliterate the region’s economy, and the Pacific Northwest may end up going months without electricity or water afterwards.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Location of the Cascadia fault line2. Juan de Fuca oceanic plate moving against the North American plate3. Plate moving underneath the North American plate4. North American plate sinking5. Region that will receive the greatest impact6. Frequency of Cascadia earthquakesVOICEOVER (in English): “A massive earthquake is expected to occur at the Cascadia subduction zone, a fault line that runs from Cape Mendocino in northern California to Vancouver Island, Canada.” “Next to the fault line is Juan de Fuca, an oceanic plate that continuously pushes against the North American continental plate.”“When the Juan de Fuca plate slides under the North American plate…” “... it will cause an earthquake. The entire coastal area will sink at least six feet in less than five minutes.”“Northern California and Oregon are expected to receive the greatest impact from the massive quake.”“There is usually a large quake along the fault every 300 years. As the last Cascadia earthquake took place on January 26, 1700, the Pacific Northwest is long overdue for a giant earthquake.”SOURCES: Southwest Neighborhoods, Inc., The New Yorker, Oregon State Universityhttp://swni.org/ep/cascadiahttp://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2015/07/20/the-really-big-onehttps://ceoas.oregonstate.edu/features/pnwearthquakerisk/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
