      <title>Science solves dishwasher loading dispute</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twExperts working at Birmingham University’s Department of Chemical Engineering say the best way to pack a dishwasher is in a circular pattern with cutlery in the center.Dishes used for protein-heavy foods should sit on the edges and be placed lower in the machine to allow enough time for chemical detergents to effectively work, the researchers said, while plates and dishes used for carbohydrate-based foods should be packed in the center of trays or on top shelves to be closer to water jet sprays that dislodge these food remnants.  Water in a dishwasher travels at a higher velocity towards the center of the machine and at a lower velocity along the edges. The slower-moving detergent-filled water breaks down proteins, while the faster-moving water swirling around the outside edges of the dishwasher helps break up and clean away carbohydrate-type foods.Media reported researchers also noted that rinsing dishes before washing them is unnecessary and simply scraping off excess food is sufficient.They also explained that that an overloaded dishwasher cannot properly clean dishes as there is not enough room between items to ensure dish surfaces come in contact with water and are cleaned properly.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. A dishwashing machine is x-rayed as dishes enter the machine in a circular pattern. 2. A dish containing protein-based food is placed in the recommended location. 3. A dish containing carbohydrate-based food is placed in the recommended location.4. X-ray shows water traveling at higher and lower velocities inside the machine. 5. An inside look of the dishwashing machine shows water moving at varying velocities which has an effect on dirty dishes inside the machine. 6. The effects of an overloaded dishwasher. VOICEOVER (in English): “Experts working at Birmingham University’s Department of Chemical Engineering  earlier this year said that the best way to pack a dishwasher is in a circular pattern with cutlery in the center.”“Dishes used for protein heavy foods should sit on the edges and be placed lower in the machine to allow enough time for chemical detergents to effectively work.” “Dishes used for carbohydrate-based foods should be packed in the center of trays or on top shelves to be closer to water jet sprays that dislodge these food remnants.”  “Water in a dishwasher travels at a higher velocity towards the center of the machine and at a lower velocity along the edges.” “Slower-moving detergent-filled water breaks down proteins, while faster-moving water helps break up and clean away carbohydrate type foods.”“When a dishwasher is overloaded there is not enough room between items to ensure dish surfaces come in contact with water and are cleaned properly.”  SOURCES: The Wall Street Journal, The Daily Mailhttp://www.wsj.com/articles/youre-loading-the-dishwasher-wrong-a-chore-and-a-power-struggle-1435682078http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3158188/Finally-advice-save-marriage-experts-say-stack-dishwasher.html***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
