      <title>Technical trouble at United Airlines, The Wall Street Journal and the NYSE</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twTechnological problems at United Airlines, the Wall Street Journal and the New York Stock Exchange have ignited fears about cybersecurity and raised concerns about the vulnerabilities of many of the nation’s Internet-based systems.A series of internal technical issues that cropped up on Wednesday grounded United Airlines flights for several hours, downed the Wall Street Journal’s website and halted trade in the New York Stock Exchange.While none of the issues were due to cyberattacks, Wednesday’s events have sparked fears that many Internet-based systems are vulnerable to hackers. As the world has become increasingly connected to the Internet, more and more of the vital systems people use are Internet-reliant, and therefore potentially more vulnerable.Problems with the Internet are inevitable, and there’s always the potential for broken codes, human error and cyberattacks that mess with the system. Carl Wright, general manager of TrapX, a security company told the Los Angeles Times that a company could better protect their system by using two internet providers rather than one, with one serving as the backup. The company could also increase their security budget and train employees on how to handle internet failures quickly.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Technical issues at United Airlines, the Wall Street Journal and the NYSE2. World becoming more dependent on the Internet3. Hacker targeting an internet-based system 4. Current spendings on technological security5. Ways to strengthen a company’s internet-based systemVOICEOVER (in English): “As the New York Stock Exchange tweeted yesterday, the issues were ‘not the result of a cyber breach,’ but the problems have still ignited fears about cybersecurity in the U.S.”“A series of technical issues that cropped up on Wednesday grounded United Airlines flights for several hours, downed the Wall Street Journal’s website and halted trade in the New York Stock Exchange.”  “Many of the world’s systems are increasingly Internet-reliant.”“Problems with the Internet are inevitable, and there’s always the potential for broken codes, human error and cyber attacks that disrupt with the system.”“However, the Los Angeles Times reports that many companies spend as little as 6 percent of their IT budget on security, leaving their systems vulnerable to issues.”“To better protect their system, a company could use two Internet providers rather than one, with one serving as the backup. The company could also increase their security budget and train employees on how to handle internet failures quickly.”SOURCES: http://www.latimes.com/business/technology/la-fi-tn-technical-problems-united-nyse-20150708-story.htmlhttp://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-nyse-outage-may-not-matter-to-investors-1436374396http://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2015/07/wall-street-journal-website-down-amid-nyse-united-210137.html***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
