      <title>Japanese weather satellite goes active</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.tw　A Japanese weather satellite that was launched to forecast typhoon movements and heavy rainfall went into operation today.The Himawari-8 was launched into geostationary orbit in October of 2014. It can capture images much faster and at a higher resolution than its predecessor, the Himawari-7. The Himawari-8 can take pictures every two minutes and 30 seconds, compared to once every 30-minutes for the Himawari-7.The full-color images taken by the Himawari-8 will allow scientists to more easily differentiate between cloud formations and yellow sand dust clouds, and help officials make more accurate weather forecasts and prepare for dangerous weather conditions. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Himawari-8 was launched in October of 20142. Himawari-8 went into operation at 11 a.m. today Japanese time 3. Himawari-8 can capture images much faster and at a higher resolution 4. Himawari-8 allows for more accurate weather forecasts and disaster prevention5. Himawari-8 identifies yellow dust clouds and clouds via color footageVOICEOVER (in English): “Japan’s Himawari-8 weather satellite was launched in October of 2014.”“Since then, the satellite has been in orbit, but it goes into full operation today.”“The satellite has a much clearer resolution than its predecessor, and can take pictures every two minutes and 30 seconds. Previously, the Himawari-7 was only able to snap pictures in 30-minutes intervals.”“The technology allows officials to make more accurate weather forecasts as well as become more prepared for dangerous weather conditions.”“The color images taken by the satellite also allow scientists to more easily differentiate between cloud formations and yellow sand dust clouds.”SOURCES: http://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20150707/k10010141351000.htmlhttp://www.huffingtonpost.jp/tenkijp/triple-typhoon_b_7734878.htmlhttp://www.47news.jp/CN/201507/CN2015070701000989.htmlhttp://www.data.jma.go.jp/mscweb/ja/himawar