      <title>Japan early industrial sites win UNESCO heritage status</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twJapan won UNESCO World Cultural Heritage status for 23 Meiji Industrial Revolution sites on Sunday.The sites, including Hashima Island, also known as Battleship Island, a coal mine island off Nagasaki Port, illustrate Japan’s rapid industrialisation.South Korea says many of the sites employed forced labour from the Korean Peninsula. Due to disagreements with South Korea over the recognition of the forced labor issue, the assessment was delayed by a day until Sunday the 5th.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1.Steel, shipbuilding, coal facilities and 8 Prefectures and 23 sites (including 2 sites in Kumamoto Prefecture) are certified as World Heritage Sites.2.The introduction of western industrialization in Japan.3.South Korea insisted that "the Korean Peninsula-born people were engaged in forced labor."4.Consultations between Japan and South Korea, on July 4th the assessment was postponed to July 5th.5.Japan has 15 registered cultural sites, , including the natural sites sums up a total of 19 sites.VOICEOVER (in English): Twenty-three sites in 8 prefectures from the Meiji Industrial Revolution have been recognized, including steel, shipbuilding, and coal mining facilities. The sites were recognised for their key role in bringing industrialization to Japan.South Korea says large numbers of Koreans were employed at the sites as forced labour. Due to disagreements with South Korea over the recognition of the forced labor issue, the assessment was delayed by a day until Sunday the 5th.Japan now has 15 registered UNESCO cultural sites, and 19 sites in total. SOURCES: http://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20150705/k10010139851000.htmlhttp://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/html/20150706/k10010140011000.htmlhttp://www.yomiuri.co.jp/culture/20150705-OYT1T50086.htmlhttp://www.huffingtonpost.jp/2015/07/05/world-heritage-gunkanjima_n_7730182.html?utm_hp_ref=japanhttp://www.47news.jp/CN/201507/CN2015070501001437.htmlhttp