      <title>Tokyo&#x2019;s Haneda Airport to begin using robots</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twIn September, the Tokyo city airport will lease 11 robots to help clean the facilities and carry passengers’ baggage, according to multiple reports. The robots look similar to wet-dry vacuums or motorized stools. Authorities say if the robots work well, more airports around the country may also begin to use them.“I want to expand it to all other airports in Japan, and also to airports worldwide,” Bloomberg quoted Japan Airport Terminal Co. President Isao Takashiro as saying. The airport operator leased the robots from Cyberdyne Inc., the two companies said in a statement released Thursday.Cyberdyne will also provide five exoskeletons designed to help workers in loading tasks. The company says the suits work by detecting electric signals from the wearer’s brain to help people move merchandise more easily.The announcement of robots in the airport comes after Japan’s Cabinet’s Tuesday approval of the government’s revamped Japan Revitalization Strategy, which includes support for robot research and development as one of the main areas of focus.As Japan’s workforce ages, robots are beginning to take over the work. According to Bloomberg, about 26 percent of Japan’s 127 million population are aged over 65. This is the highest percentage among the top seven industrialized nations.Haneda is the second-busiest airport in Asia and the fourth-busiest in the world, according to the International Air Transport Association.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Demonstration of exoskeleton 2. Continued demonstration of exoskeleton 3. Demonstration of robots at airport4. Disabled passenger unable to lift bags5. Robots helps passenger carry bags6. Depiction of all the robots that will be usedVOICEOVER (in English): “An exoskeleton that fits over airport workers’ bodies and interprets signals from their brains will help Haneda Airport staff in moving heavy merchandise.”“Robots that are designed to clean the facilities at the airport 24 hours a day will also be deployed.”“Meanwhile, robots capable of supporting 200 kg in weight will be used to aid passengers who are unable to carry their own luggage.”“Officials say the use of the robots will help reduce costs, and the program may possibly be expanded to other airports.”SOURCES: Bloomberg, Nikkei, NTV, TBS, Sankei, Japan Times, Kyodo Newshttp://www.bloomberg.co.jp/news/123-NQUPNF6JTSEB01.html http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-07-02/say-konnichi-wa-to-robots-in-tokyo-ahttp://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXLASDZ02HSK_S5A700C1TI5000/http://toyokeizai.net/articles/-/75530http://news.tbs.co.jp/newseye/tbs_newseye2531214.htmlhttp://www.sankeibiz.jp/business/news/150703/bsd1507030500003-n1.htmhttp://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/07/02/business/tech/haneda-airport-used-testing-ground-robot-technology/#.VZW8VvntlBchttp://www.kyodonews.net/news/2015/07/02/22918***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
