      <title>Toshiba to use scorpion-like robot to enter Fukushima nuclear power plant</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twToshiba is deploying a robot that looks like a scorpion to enter the Fukushima Dai-ichi nuclear power plant in Japan. This comes amid the ongoing struggle to clean up the power plant following the 2011 earthquake and tsunami in northern Japan that caused a radiation leak and long-term evacuations.The cylinder-shaped machine was developed with the International Research Institute for Nuclear Decommissioning (IRID), and is designed to enter the primary containment vessel (PCV) of the Unit 2 reactor at the plant.The aim of the device is to help authorities determine the condition and location of melted-down fuel in the reactor, which is too dangerous for workers to enter.The robot is 54 centimetres long and is able to pull itself right-side up if it falls over. A joint near the middle of the robot allows it to raise its tail like a scorpion to allow a camera and LED lights to sweep the environment. This complements another camera and LED lights in the nose section of the robot.Control signals are sent to the robot through a wire by operators using devices resembling PlayStation game controllers. The 5-kilogram (11-pound) machine also has a thermometer and a dosimeter, and can withstand about 100 Sieverts per hour of radiation for 10 hours.The robot could be exposed to as much as 70 Sieverts per hour of radiation in the No. 2 reactor. This is about seven times that encountered by robots that ventured into the No. 1 reactor, according to a Toshiba spokeswoman.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Conditions inside Fukushima nuclear power plant2. Depiction of robot3. Interior of robot4. Operators controlling robot5. Robot navigating6. Proposed date robot will be deployedVOICEOVER (in English): “A cylinder-shaped machine is designed to enter a primary containment vessel of the Fukushima Dai-ichi Nuclear Power Plant.”“The robot, measuring 26 centimetres along the base, can withstand about 100 Sieverts per hour of radiation for 10 hours.”“A camera and LED lights located on the robot’s tail allow it to visually sweep the environment.”“This is controlled by operators who send signals to the robot through a wire.”“Even in low visibility conditions, the robot can identify obstructions within a range of 3 metres.”“Experts will begin testing the device in July, with the robot expected to be deployed into the nuclear power plant in August.”SOURCES: http://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXLASGG30H0I_Q5A630C1000000/http://www.nikkan.co.jp/news/nkx0120150701bcak.htmlhttp://news.tv-asahi.co.jp/news_economy/articles/000053735.htmlhttp://www.computerworld.com/article/2942037/emerging-technology/toshiba-readies-scorpionlike-robot-for-fukushima-nuclear-plant.html***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
