      <title>SpaceX rocket explodes after launch</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twAn unmanned SpaceX rocket exploded shortly after launch from Florida on Sunday, destroying supplies bound for the International Space Station.The cause of explosion in the Falcon 9 rocket was not yet clear, officials told Reuters. A preliminary analysis indicated a problem with the rocket's upper-stage engine, Space X CEO Elon Musk said on Twitter.Falcon 9 rockets will be grounded  for "a number of months or so" but less than a year while an investigation into the explosion is conducted, SpaceX President Gwynne Shotwell said.The Falcon 9 rocket has flown 18 times successfully since its debut five years ago. These include six station cargo runs for NASA under a 15-fight contract worth more than $2 billion. RUNDOWN SHOWS: 1. Falcon 9 rocket2. Rocket separating from payload3. Supplies4. International space station5. Astronaut and Cosmonauts aboard space stationVOICEOVER (in English): “Officials are trying to ascertain what caused a SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket to explode after liftoff on Sunday. Preliminary analysis indicates an oxygen tank malfunction.”“If the launch was successful, the unmanned rocket would have continued into orbit, eventually separating from its payload.”“The craft was carrying supplies bound for the International Space Station. These included food44, hardware, an international docking adapter and other materials.“Reuters reports that the mission is the second unsuccessful mission this year to resupply the space station, though this is the first failed attempt by SpaceX.”“Aboard the station right now are two Russians and one American. They have around four months of supplies left.”SOURCES: Reuters, CNNhttp://www.reuters.com/article/2015/06/28/us-space-spacex-launch-idUSKCN0P80NM20150628http://money.cnn.com/2015/06/28/technology/spacex-failed-mission-what-we-know/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, plea