      <title>Japanese carmakers expand recall of cars with Takata airbags</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twJapanese carmakers Toyota, Nissan and Mitsubishi are recalling more cars to replace airbags made by Takata, which have been linked to eight deaths and more than 100 injuries.Takata is at the center of a recall of tens of millions of cars around the world for potentially deadly air bag inflators that could deploy with too much force and spray metal fragments inside vehicles.The recalls initially were limited to North America but now how been expanded to cover the rest of the world.The faulty airbags are found in certain models made by Toyota, Honda, Mazda, BMW, Nissan, Mitsubishi, Subaru, Chrysler, Ford and General Motors.The inside of an airbag’s inflator assembly, which is located underneath the steering wheel, is filled with propellant granules and propellants. Unlike propellants made by most other brands, Takata-designed propellants are made from ammonium nitrate. If exposed to high humidity, the propellants can end up damaged or cracked, this causes them to produce too much pressure inside the inflator, causing it to crack and explode.When the airbag inflates, pieces of the damaged inflator may fly at the driver and passenger like shrapnel, putting people in a crash at greater risk of injury. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Passenger and driver-side airbags experience problems2. Location of an inflator assembly and propellant granules within the inflator heating up the propellants3. Propellant exposed to high humidity and causing damage to the inflator4. Airbag inflating and pieces of the inflator hitting the driver VOICEOVER (in English): “The recalled vehicles feature front passenger and driver-side airbags that may deploy abnormally, according to Takata.”“The inside of an airbag’s inflator assembly, which is located underneath the steering wheel, is filled with propellant granules and propellants. Unlike propellants made by most other brands, Takata-designed propellants are made from ammonium nitrate.”“If exposed to high humidity, the propellants can end up damaged, which causes them to produce too much pressure inside the inflator, causing it to crack and explode.” “When the airbag inflates, pieces of the damaged inflator may fly at the driver and passenger like shrapnel, putting people involved in a crash at greater risk of injury.”SOURCES: Reuters, National Highway and Traffic Safety Administration, NBC News, New York Times, ABC Newshttp://www.reuters.com/article/2015/06/25/us-autos-takata-idUSKBN0P503D20150625http://www.nhtsa.gov/About+NHTSA/Press+Releases/2014/Vehicle-owners-with-defective-airbags-urged-to-take-immediate-actionhttp://www.nbcnews.com/business/autos/u-s-expands-recall-warning-cars-defective-air-bags-n231216http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/10/21/us-autos-takata-lawsuits-idUSKCN0IA1TK20141021 http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/10/22/us-autos-takata-warning-idUSKCN0IB03B20141022http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/10/22/us-autos-takata-warning-idUSKCN0IB03B20141022http://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/20/business/takata-airbag-recall.html?_r=0http://abcnews.go.com/US/takata-corp-declares-34-million-airbags-defective-agrees/story?id=31157446***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
