      <title>Woman gets flesh-eating bacteria after mud run</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twA Texas woman is now blind in one eye after she was infected with flesh-eating bacteria while competing in a mud run in Dallas earlier this month.Brittany Williams from north Texas became infected with flesh-eating bacteria in her eye during a mud run in Dallas. Within 24 hours the bacteria had destroyed her cornea.“My eye started hurting, like maybe I’ve got mud or some debris in there,” Brittany Williams told CBS DFW. “When I opened my eye, it was just like white. The whole room was white.”Flesh-eating bacteria is an infection caused by the bacterium Streptococcus pyogenes. The bacteria can enter the human body through minor cuts or abrasions. It then produces toxins that destroy tissues such as muscles, skin and fat, according to MedicineNet.com.Williams has two jobs but no health insurance. Her family has set up a fundraising campaign to raise money to cover her $100,000 medical bills, CBS DFW reported.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Streptococcus pyogenes bacteria floating in midair2. Bacteria enters skin via an open wound3. Bacteria destroy tissues4. A debris cut William’s eye5. Bacteria destroy her corneaVOICEOVER (in English): “Flesh-eating bacteria is an infection caused by the bacterium Streptococcus pyogenes.”“The bacteria can enter human body through minor cuts or abrasions. Once inside the body the bacteria produces toxins that destroy tissue such as muscles, skin and fat.”“Brittany Williams caught flesh-eating bacteria after cutting her eye during a Dallas mud run around two weeks ago…” “.... and within 24 hours the bacteria had destroyed her cornea.’SOURCES: CBS DFW, MedicineNet.comhttp://dfw.cbslocal.com/2015/06/22/dirty-and-dangerous-woman-loses-sight-in-eye-after-mud-run/http://www.medicinenet.com/flesh_eating_bacterial_infection/views.htm***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841