      <title>New technology would make houses hover during earthquakes</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twGreg Henderson, the co-founder and CEO of Arx Pax, says electromagnetic hoverboard technology may be the future of earthquake-proofed homes.Most earthquake-proofing systems decouple buildings from the ground using “base isolation bearings” so that they can move freely without compromising the building’s integrity.Henderson’s new system would rely on an electromagnet to produce repulsive magnetic force and generate lift.The house would be linked to the U.S. Geological Survey’s ShakeAlert system, allowing it to retract landing gears, activate the electromagnet and hover for up to 90 seconds when an earthquake is detected.The ShakeAlert system, which relies on a series of sensors placed near fault lines, has already proven effective in giving residents of earthquake-prone areas a head-start on incoming quakes.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Normal house destroyed in earthquake2. Base isolation bearings3. Arx Pax’s new patent4. Electromagnets5. Electromagnetic house6. ShakeAlert systemVOICEOVER (in English): “During an earthquake, the main danger to a building’s structure is lateral movement.”“Today, most earthquake-proofing systems decouple buildings from the ground using ‘base isolation bearings’ so that they can move freely without compromising the building’s integrity.”“Arx Pax currently hold a patent for a buffer system that uses water or gas to raise homes, protecting them from destructive lateral movement.”“But Henderson’s new system would rely on electromagnetics to produce repulsive magnetic force and lift the house.”“The house would be linked to the U.S. Geological Survey’s ShakeAlert system, allowing activate the electromagnet and hover for up to 90-seconds when an earthquake is detected.”“The ShakeAlert system, which relies on a series of sensors placed near fault lines, has already proven effective in giving residents of earthquake-prone areas a head start on incoming earthquakes”SOURCES: http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-3119169/Could-hover-houses-protect-California-big-one-Firm-reveals-plans-raise-homes-giant-magnets-event-quake.htmlhttp://www.theverge.com/2014/10/21/7025197/i-rode-a-real-hoverboardhttp://www.foxnews.com/tech/2015/06/10/california-company-aims-to-hover-buildings/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
