      <title>Philae comet lander wakes up after seven months</title>
      <description><![CDATA[The Philae comet lander that lost contact with Earth after landing on a comet late last year has woken up and is now communicating with Earth.The Philae probe landed on comet 67P in mid November 2014, but ran out of power shortly afterwards because its solar panels could not pick up enough sunlight after it landed in the shadow of a cliff, according to the Telegraph.As 67P approaches the Sun, Philae’s solar panels have been able to absorb enough sunlight to communicate with the Rosetta probe that is in orbit around the comet. A signal from Philae was picked up on Saturday night and continued for 85 seconds, the Telegraph reported.“It's been a long seven months, and to be quite honest we weren't sure it would happen - there are a lot of very happy people around Europe at the moment,” the Telegraph quoted European Space Agency scientist Mark McCaughrean as saying.The mission was due to end in September but the European Space Agency said it would likely run to 2016, the Telegraph reported.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Location of the comet when Philae lost power in Nov 20142. Location of the comet when Philae makes contact in June 20153. Philae sending signals to Rosetta for 85 seconds4. Illustration of the comet and how it will be nearest to the Sun in August5. The comet throws out dust and gas as it approaches the SunVOICEOVER (in English): “The Philae probe landed on comet 67P in mid November 2014, but ran out of power shortly afterwards as its solar panels could not pick up enough sunlight as it landed in the shadow of a cliff.”“As the comet 67P approaches the Sun, Philae’s solar panels were able absorb enough sunlight to restart communications with the Rosetta probe that has been orbiting the comet.” “A signal from Philae was picked up on Saturday night and it continued for 85 seconds.”“Comet 67P is currently 205 million km from the Sun. It will be at the nearest point to the Sun in August.”“The comet is expected to become more active and could interfere with Philae’s communication with Rosetta as it approaches the Sun.”SOURCES: The Telegraph, European Space Agencyhttp://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/science/space/11673849/Philae-Europes-comet-lander-wakes-up.htmlhttp://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/science/space/11195744/The-Rosetta-mission-everything-you-need-to-know-about-the-quest-to-catch-a-comet.htmlhttp://www.esa.int/Our_Activities/Operations/Rosetta_operations***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
