      <title>U.S. plans to store heavy arms in Baltic, Eastern Europe</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twThe U.S. in planning to store military equipment in eastern Europe to build up the region’s defense capabilities. If the Pentagon’s proposal is approved, it will be the first time Washington has stationed heavy weaponry in countries once under Russia’s sphere of influence.No final decision has yet been made, but the Pentagon plans to store equipment in Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania, as well as in Poland, Hungary, Romania and Bulgaria. If the proposal is approved, enough equipment for 150 soldiers will be stored in each of the Baltic states and enough for 750 soldiers will be stored in the four other eastern European ones. The Pentagon estimates that it will store about 1,200 armored vehicles in the region, including M1-A2 tanks, Bradley fighting vehicles and armored howitzers.The Pentagon also plans to build railways and warehouses to accommodate the new, American weaponry in the NATO member states. The warehouses will be guarded by local contractors, rather than American military personnel.The U.S. and NATO member states have been taking steps to strengthen defense forces in the region following Russia’s annexation of Crimea and the ongoing war in eastern Ukraine.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Barrier between NATO and Russia2. Pentagon upgrading railways and warehouses in eastern Europe3. Warehouses guarded by security contractors4. Pentagon will store equipment including 1,200 armored vehicles5. Amount of equipment U.S. plans to store in eastern EuropeVOICEOVER (in English): “The U.S. plans to store heavy weaponry to reassure Baltic and Eastern European allies concerned by Russia’s intervention in Ukraine.” “The Pentagon plans to build railways and warehouses to accommodate new, American weaponry in the member states.”“The weapons warehouses will be guarded by local contractors, rather than American military personnel.”“Washington plans to store about 1,200 armored vehicles, including M1-A2 tanks, Bradley fighting vehicles and armored howitzers.” “Equipment will be stored in Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania, as well as in Poland, Hungary, Romania and Bulgaria. The equipment will be enough for 150 soldiers in each of the Baltic states and 750 soldiers in the four other states.”SOURCES: Reuters, The New York Times, RThttp://www.reuters.com/article/2015/06/14/us-usa-military-europe-idUSKBN0OT0TR20150614http://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/14/world/europe/us-poised-to-put-heavy-weaponry-in-east-europe.htmlhttp://rt.com/news/267106-us-poland-weapons-deployment/http://rt.com/news/267031-us-heavy-weapons-baltics/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
