      <title>US EPA moves toward regulating aircraft emissions</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twThe U.S. Environmental Protection Agency issued a draft scientific finding on Wednesday on how aircraft emissions contribute to climate change. The findings serve as the foundation for the EPA’s proposal to begin regulating aircraft emissions.The EPA’s findings, the so-called “endangerment finding,” is a precursor to the EPA’s proposal to curb emissions from commercial aircraft. The EPA plans to partner with the United Nations’ International Civil Aviation Organization and develop worldwide carbon dioxide standards for planes. The United Nations is scheduled to release its proposed emissions standards by February 2016. Commercial aircraft contribute 11 percent of emissions in the U.S. transportation sector, and make up three percent of total U.S. emissions. While car emissions are already regulated in the U.S., and power plant emissions will be soon come under the Clean Power Plan, the airline industry still goes largely unchecked.The UN and the EPA’s carbon dioxide standards are expected to apply only to new aircraft designs certified from 2020 onwards, leaving the majority of the world’s aircraft unregulated. The EPA also excluded military aircraft or small planes such as turboprops from its proposal.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. The EPA regulates car and power plant emissions but not plane emissions2. EPA starting to regulate plane emissions3. Aircraft contribution to total U.S. emissions4. Plan will not include regulating military planes and small planesVOICEOVER (in English): “Car emissions are already regulated in the U.S., and power plant emissions will soon come under the Clean Power Plan, but the airline industry remains largely unchecked.”“The EPA aims to change this by partnering with the United Nations’ International Civil Aviation Organization to develop carbon dioxide standards for planes.”“Commercial aircraft contribute 11 percent of emissions in the U.S. transportation sector, and makes up three percent of total U.S. emissions.”“The EPA has found that commercial aircraft contribute to climate change and seeks to regulate their emissions. However, the EPA has not mentioned the impact of military aircraft or small planes such as turboprops.”SOURCES: The Washington Post, CNN, The Wall Street Journal, USA Todayhttp://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2015/06/10/epa-moves-toward-limits-on-emissions-from-u-s-airlines/http://edition.cnn.com/2015/06/10/politics/epa-regulating-airplane-emissions/http://www.wsj.com/articles/obama-administration-to-take-aim-at-airline-emissions-1433946834http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2015/06/10/epa-airlines-greenhouse-gas-emissions-a4a-iata-icao/28487755/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
