      <title>Home batteries from Tesla and Mercedes-Benz help spread distributed power generation</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twNew large-capacity batteries for home use from companies such as Tesla and Mercedes-Benz are increasing the viability of renewable energy for distributed generation. Solar energy is gaining popularity, with several U.S. states providing large subsidies to homeowners who install solar panels, but so far integrating it into the power grid has been a problem. Most energy still comes from centralized power plants, with home-generated solar energy being used or sold to the grid as it is produced. No solar energy is produced at night.  During the hot summer months, power utilities produce more energy and charge more during peak hours in the middle of the day. Other than fuel, the utilities’ main expenses are from maintaining the grid itself.With a home battery, homes with solar panels can save their own power during the day, and homes without solar panels can store cheap power from off-peak hours at night. Unused energy stored in the batteries can be sold back to the grid during peak hours. If home renewable energy generation and home battery storage became widespread, power plants could reduce their excess generation capacity. Power utilities would primarily be in the business of maintaining the grid, and the flow of energy from utility to customer would no longer be a one-way street. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Home solar only working during daylight 2. Power plant burning coal at peak time3. Houses use peak power for air conditioning in summer4. Utilities responsible for maintaining grid5. Home batteries can store solar power or cheap off-peak power6. Battery houses can use stored energy at peak time7. Solar and battery equipped homes sell power back to grid at peak8. When batteries and solar panels are ubiquitous, power plant burns less coal9. Utility still responsible for maintaining grid10. Less coal required, energy market now a two way streetVOICEOVER (in English): “Solar energy is increasing in popularity, but so far integrating it into the power grid has been a problem. Most energy comes from power plants, with home-generated solar energy being used or sold to the grid as it is produced, and none is produced at night.”  “Power utilities burn fuel to produce electricity. They produce more and charge more during peak hours in the middle of the day. Other than fuel, their main expenses are from maintaining the grid itself.” “Now, large home batteries are being marketed for homes with renewable generation, to save their own power, and to regular homes, so they can store cheap power from off-peak hours. Excess capacity can even be sold back to the grid during peak hours.” “With ubiquitous home renewable energy generation, and home battery storage, power plants can reduce their excess generation capacity. Power utilities will primarily be in the business of maintaining the grid. The flow of energy will no longer be a one-way street.” SOURCES: Bloomberg, Engadget, Power-eng.com,http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-06-08/elon-musk-says-utilities-shouldn-t-fear-his-battery-systemshttp://www.engadget.com/2015/06/09/mercedes-benz-home-battery/http://www.power-eng.com/blogs/power-points/2015/01/the_debate_over_dist.html***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
