      <title>Britain approves world&#x2019;s first tidal lagoon power project</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twBritain has given the go ahead for a 1 billion pound tidal power plant in Wales' Swansea Bay, the Department of Energy and Climate Change said on Tuesday. The project, developed by Tidal Lagoon Power, is expected to generate enough electricity to power around 155,000 homes. The project will create a 750-meter-long lagoon-shaped seawall in Swansea Bay and use the difference in water levels between the sea and the water inside the lagoon. Up to 26 low-head bulb turbines will be installed inside concrete turbine housings that are permanently submerged. Each turbine is equipped with sluice gates that will remain closed until the water level on either side is high enough to pass through and generate electricity. Hence, the process can be operated on flood tides as well as ebb tides. Developers say that this is the first step towards producing 10 percent of UK’s energy from tides. According to Bloomberg Business, Tidal Lagoon Power has started planning a second project: a second tidal power plant that can generate enough electricity for every home in Wales. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Top view of the lagoon in Swansea Bay2. Illustrating the construction of the lagoon wall3. Illustrating the capacity of the turbine housings4. Illustrating the process of generating power on the flood tide5. Illustrating the process of generating power on the ebb tideVOICEOVER (in English):“The project will create a 750-meter-long lagoon-shaped seawall in Swansea Bay.”“The wall will be made from hydraulically filled geotextile tubes and compact sand fill. Layers of rocks will be added on top to protect the wall from degradation.”“Concrete turbine housings will hold up to 26 low-head bulb turbines that are permanently submerged. Each turbine can generate up to 16 megawatts per hour.”“The turbines’ sluice gates will be closed until the water level outside the lagoon is high enough. It will then open to let the water flows into the lagoon through the turbines to generating electricity.”“This process then occurs in reverse on the ebb tide.” SOURCES: IEEE Spectrum, Wales Online, This is South Wales, Reuters, Sky News, Bloomberg Businesshttp://spectrum.ieee.org/green-tech/geothermal-and-tidal/tidal-power-makes-a-surprising-comebackhttp://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/business/business-news/tidal-lagoon-power-signed-mou-4035952http://www.thisissouthwales.co.uk/Swansea-Bay-tidal-lagoon-report-works-access/story-19307111-detail/story.html#axzz2WlX2gq2yhttp://uk.reuters.com/article/2015/06/09/uk-britain-wavepower-lagoon-idUKKBN0OP1VW20150609http://news.sky.com/story/1499090/uk-to-get-underwater-power-stationhttp://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-06-09/u-k-tidal-lagoon-project-in-swansea-wins-planning-permission***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
