      <title>Malaysia to lodge protest over Chinese coast guard &#x201C;intrusion&#x201D;</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twA Chinese coast guard vessel spotted anchored 93 miles north of Malaysia is causing diplomatic tension between the two pacific nations.Malaysia’s national security minister Shahid Kassim said the country would protest what it called an intrusion by the Chinese ship.The Malaysian government said the Chinese ship was spotted anchored near Luconia Shoals, a series of islets within an exclusive economic zone claimed by Malaysia.Hong Lei, a spokesman for China’s Ministry of Foreign Affairs, said he did “not have knowledge” of the case and declined to offer further comment.Last year China conducted naval exercises near the James Shoal reef, also claimed by Malaysia, prompting the country to change tact in dealings Beijing, senior diplomats told Reuters.China in recent years has caused regional tensions with its claims to virtually all of the South China Sea that cover approximately 1.35 million square miles of the area.Vietnam, the Philippines, Taiwan and Brunei all also have competing claims to various areas of the South China Sea.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Malaysia and China2. Chinese vessel at Luconia Shoal3. South China Sea claims by Malaysia and China4. Chinese naval exercises at the James Shoal reef5. South China Sea claims by Vietnam, Philippines and BruneiVOICEOVER (in English): Malaysia’s national security minister said the country would protest what it called an intrusion by a Chinese coast guard ship close to Borneo.Malaysia said the Chinese ship was spotted anchored near Luconia Shoals, a series of islets within an exclusive economic zone claimed by Malaysia.China in recent years has caused regional tensions with its claims over virtually all of the South China Sea.Last year China conducted naval exercises near the James Shoal reef, also claimed by Malaysia, prompting the country to change tact in dealings Beijing, senior diplomats told Reuters.Vietnam, the Philippines and Brunei all also have competing claims to various parts of the South China Sea.SOURCES: Reuters, Wall Street Journalhttp://www.reuters.com/article/2015/06/09/us-southchinasea-malaysia-china-idUSKBN0OP06120150609http://www.wsj.com/articles/malaysia-toughens-stance-with-beijing-over-south-china-sea-1433764608***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
