      <title>Drone that can fly forever patented by Boeing</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twBoeing obtained a patent for a drone and related charging system on June 2 that would allow the aircraft to remain aloft indefinitely. Titled “Autonomous aircraft with disconnectable tether,” Boeing’s patent describes a lighter-than-air craft that connects to charging towers. The design would reduce the system’s footprint from the long airstrip required by fixed wing drones down to the area of a charging tower, which could be situated in populated areas the way communications towers are.Boeing’s patent describes a buoyant aircraft that can navigate to a ground-based power supply, then lower a tether that latches onto the power supply. The craft’s control system can then order the tether to disengage after charging is complete. The power supply end of the system could be attached to a land-based tower, a high-altitude tethered balloon, a ship at sea or a terrestrial vehicle. The drone would lower its own tether down to the power supply, similar to the probe-and-drogue system used by planes for air-to-air refueling. Drones using this charging technology could find applications in parcel delivery, surveillance or other tasks where landing frequently would be impractical. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Balloon drone flying over city2. Balloon drone connecting to charging tower3. Balloon drone battery charging complete4. Cityscape with balloon drones charging and flying5. Balloon drone charging from Navy ship or public bus6. Balloon drone charging from a tethered balloon in the sky7. Balloon drone delivering a package without landing8. Winged drone taking off and landing at same airport9. Helicopter drone unable to travel same distance on one charge10. Winged drone unable to monitor ocean area for long, balloon drone monitors continuously11. Balloon drone dispatched from office roof with a package12. Balloon drone arriving at private home to deliver packageVOICEOVER (in English): “Boeing has obtained a patent for a type of drone that could potentially fly forever. The patent describes a lighter than air craft, which charges via tether while remaining aloft.” “When the drone receives a signal, it detaches from the charging tether and changes location. The drones could also be charged via a ship, a moving land vehicle, or a high-altitude balloon.” “The system address two drawbacks of traditional drones. Fixed-wing drones require a runway to take off and must return to base to recharge. Vertical-takeoff drones have limited range and cumbersome landing gear.” “The floating drones could provide persistent monitoring of an area or rapid delivery service without needing to land.” SOURCES: Geekwire, U.S. Patent Office,http://www.geekwire.com/2015/new-patent-shows-how-boeing-plans-to-recharge-drones-in-mid-air/http://patft.uspto.gov/netacgi/nph-Parser?Sect1=PTO1&Sect2=HITOFF&d=PALL&p=1&u=%2Fnetahtml%2FPTO%2Fsrchnum.htm&r=1&f=G&l=50&s1=9045218.PN.&OS=PN/9045218&RS=PN/9045218***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
