      <title>Israel tests &#x2018;dirty bombs&#x2019; in the Negev Desert</title>
      <description><![CDATA[Israel carried out a four-year series of tests on nuclear explosives to measure the effects were “hostile forces” ever to use them against Israel, Israel’s Haaretz daily newspaper reported Monday.Between 2010 and 2014, Israel conducted tests on “dirty bombs” in the Negev Desert. The project, supervised by staff from Israel’s Dimona nuclear facility, included 20 detonations mostly in the desert and involved between 250 grams and 25 kilograms of explosives. “Dirty bombs” combine radioactive material with conventional explosives such as dynamite and are usually detonated using a battery. After the explosives were detonated, mini-drones were used to measure the radiation levels of the explosions. The tests found high-level radiation near the center of the blasts, while low-level particles further from the blast center weren’t found to pose any danger.Israel began conducting drills on how to respond to a radioactive attack after Al-Qaeda started threatening to use ‘dirty bombs’ on the U.S. following the 9/11 attacks. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Components of a dirty bomb2. Employees from an Israeli nuclear reactor testing the bombs3. Tests are conducted in the Negev Desert4. Drones calculating radiation levels after the explosions5. Another type of test conducted VOICEOVER (in English): “Israel conducted several tests on ‘dirty bombs,’ which combine radioactive material with conventional explosives such as dynamite.”“Most of the tests were conducted in the Negev Desert, and were supervised by staff from Israel’s Dimona nuclear facility.”“After the explosives were detonated, mini-drones were used to measure radiation levels near the site of the explosions.”“It found high-level radiation at the center of the blasts, while lower level radiation carried by the wind was found not to pose a significant danger.”“In order to measure the impact of a radioactive substance being released in a crowded space, researchers also put radioactive material into the ventilation system of a simulated shopping mall. However, the building’s air conditioning filters caught most of the radiation.”SOURCES: Haaretz, Sputnik International, United States Nuclear Regulatory Commission, RThttp://www.haaretz.com/news/diplomacy-defense/.premium-1.660067http://sputniknews.com/middleeast/20150608/1023085033.htmlhttp://www.nrc.gov/reading-rm/doc-collections/fact-sheets/fs-dirty-bombs.htmlhttp://rt.com/news/265831-israel-tests-dirty-bomb/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
