      <title>Pentagon chief pledges $18 million for Hanoi to buy patrol boats</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twU.S. Defense Secretary Ash Carter pledged to expand the US’ military ties with Vietnam during a visit to Hai Phong on Sunday on the latest stop on his 11-day trip to Asia-Pacific.During Carter’s visit to Vietnam, he toured a Vietnamese coast guard vessel that was damaged after being rammed by a Chinese vessel during a skirmish between the two countries last year. After Carter’s visit, the Pentagon pledged $18 million to Hanoi to buy Vietnam six aluminium Metal Shark patrol vessels to help Vietnam build up its maritime defense capabilities.Taiwan, Vietnam and China have all reclaimed land in the South China Sea. However, China has outpaced other nations by reclaiming around 2,000 acres of land according to US estimates, raising concerns in the region.Vietnam has also been aggressive in its maritime claims in the disputed territories. In the Spratly Islands, Taiwan, Malaysia, China and the Philippines have all constructed military outposts, although Vietnam has the most, with 48 in total.The Pentagon has called on all countries in the region to halt their island-building efforts in disputed territories.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. China outpacing other countries in amount of land reclaimed2. Military buildup in the Spratly Islands3. Pentagon official touring Vietnamese coast guard vessel rammed by Chinese ship4. Vietnam receiving $18 million for six Metal Shark patrol vesselsVOICEOVER (in English): “Taiwan, Vietnam and China have all reclaimed land in the South China Sea. However, China has outpaced the others by reclaiming around 2,000 acres of land according to US estimates, raising concerns in the region.”“In the Spratly Islands, Taiwan, Malaysia, China and the Philippines have all constructed outposts, although Vietnam has the most, with 48 in total.”“U.S. Defense Secretary Ash Carter toured a Vietnamese coast guard vessel that was damaged after being rammed by a Chinese vessel 