      <title>NASA starts testing new lander for 2016 mission to Mars</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twNASA is testing a new stationary lander called InSight for a planned mission to Mars in March 2016.The lander, which is equipped with two gallium arsenide solar array panels, will launch from Vandenberg Air Force Base in California and land on Mars about six months later.The InSight will not rove around Mars. Instead, it will act as a stationary driller, offering NASA for the first time in-depth analysis of Mars’ underground layers.Before the mission, InSight must pass tests to show it can endure extreme temperatures and near zero air pressure. Other tests include vibration testing meant to simulate launch conditions and checking for electronic interference between different parts of the spacecraft. According to NASA, examining Mars’ deep interior could reveal how all rocky planets, including Earth, have formed and evolved.The InSight is one of several missions NASA has planned as a prelude to the eventual goal of sending astronauts to the red planet by the 2030s.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. The InSight lander size2. The lander launch location3. The lander landing on Mars4. The lander drilling Mars soil 5. The lander tested for temperature and air pressure6. The lander tested for vibrations VOICEOVER (in English): “The lander, called InSight, is about the size of a car. It’s powered by two gallium arsenide solar array panels”“InSight will launch from Vandenberg Air Force Base in California and land on Mars abAout six months later.”“The InSight will not rove around Mars. It will stay in place as a stationary driller, offering NASA in-depth analysis of the planet’s underground layers.”“But before the mission, InSight must pass several test to show it can withstand extreme temperatures and near zero air pressure.” A vibration test simulates the vibrations during launch launch conditions SOURCES: NASA, UPIhttp://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.php?feature=4601http://www.upi.com/Science_News/2015/05/27/NASA-begins-testing-Mars-lander-InSight/7241432756148/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
