      <title>Honeybee colony collapse tackled in new White House environmental strategy</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twThe Obama administration has unveiled a strategy intended to stop beehive colony collapse, after 40 percent of commercial honeybee colonies in the United States died off last winter.The White House’s plan, which was unveiled on Tuesday and is to be carried out by the USDA and EPA, includes devoting 7 million acres of federal land to pollinator habitat, reducing annual honeybee deaths to 15 percent by 2025 and returning monarch butterfly numbers from 30 million to 220 million in five years. The plan also calls for more studies of the class of pesticides known as neonicotinoids, also known as “neonics”. Research now indicates neonics may also weaken bees’ immune systems. Weaker bees are more easily killed by invasive varroa mites and poor nutrition stemming from monocultural farming practices in the U.S.  Critics of the plan say it focuses too narrowly on commercial honeybees, only one of species 4,000 of bees in North America, and that there is no specific action plan to increase monarch butterfly numbers. Some insist neonic pesticides should be banned immediately, as they have been in the European Union. Neonic defenders point out that Australia uses the pesticides yet has avoided widespread colony collapse. Some suggest Australia’s immunity may be due to the absence of invasive varroa mites in the country. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Bee on watermelon flower2. Beekeeper checking hive3. 40 percent of honeybee hives lost4. Obama plan to devote 7 million acres to pollinators 5. Bar graph, reduce honeybee hive loss to 15 percent by 20256. Boost monarch butterfly population to 220 million in five years7. Neonicotinoids explained: caterpillar bites leaf, dies; bee lives8. Varroa mite infects bee hive9. Bees losing nutrition source to farms10. Criticism that Obama plan focuses only on honey bees11. Not enough focus or research on monarch butterflies12. Neonics combined with mites in the U.S. kill more bees than neonics alone in AustraliaVOICEOVER (in English): “On Tuesday, the Obama administration unveiled a strategy intended to stop beehive colony collapse in the United States. Bees pollinate much of the agricultural food we eat, but 40 percent of commercial honeybee colonies died off last winter, putting our food supply at risk.” “The White House’s plan, to be carried out by the USDA and EPA, includes devoting 7 million acres of federal land to pollinator habitat, reducing annual honeybee deaths to 15 percent by 2025, and returning monarch butterfly numbers from 30 million to 220 million in five years.” “The plan also calls for more studies of the class of pesticides known as neonicotinoids, which kill pests, but might also weaken bee immune systems. Weaker bees are more easily killed by invasive varroa mites, and poor nutrition from monocultural farming practices.”  “Critics of the plan say it focuses too narrowly on commercial honeybees, out of 4,000 bee species in North America, and that there is no specific action plan to increase butterfly numbers.” “Finally, some insist neonic pesticides should be banned immediately, though Australia, which is free of varroa mites, uses neonics yet has avoided colony collapse.” SOURCES: Vox, Reuters, Washington Post, Office of Science and Technology Policyhttp://www.vox.com/2015/5/19/8625183/honeybees-obamahttp://blogs.reuters.com/great-debate/2015/05/19/thats-billion-with-a-bee-measuring-the-massive-cost-of-hive-collapse/http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/whats-all-the-obama-buzz-about-bees/2015/05/18/5ebd1580-fd6a-11e4-805c-c3f407e5a9e9_story.htmlhttps://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2015/05/19/announcing-new-steps-promote-pollinator-healthhttp://apps.washingtonpost.com/g/page/national/we-all-get-stung-by-bee-colony-collapse/1108/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
