      <title>US indicts six Chinese nationals for economic espionage</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twThe United States has indicted six Chinese nationals for stealing a technology used in mobile devices.The Chinese nationals, including three Tianjin University professors, are charged with stealing FBAR technology from their U.S. employers on behalf of the Chinese government, according to a statement released by the FBI’s San Francisco Division.One of the defendants, Hao Zhang, a professor at Tianjin University, was arrested at Los Angeles International Airport over the weekend while he was on his way to a conference. The other five defendants remain in China, according to the statement. FBAR technology is used in mobile devices to filter unwanted wireless signals so that the user only receives or transmits communications to specific destinations intended by the user.The defendants could face up to 15 years’ imprisonment if convicted.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Illustration of six Chinese nationals stealing U.S. mobile phone technology2. FBAR technology blocks unwanted signals3. Defendant arrested in Los Angeles4. The other five defendants remain in ChinaVOICEOVER (in English): “Six Chinese nationals, including three Tianjin University professors, were charged with stealing FBAR technology from their U.S. employers on behalf of the Chinese government.” “FBAR technology is used in mobile devices to filter unwanted wireless signals so that the user only receives or transmits communications to specific destinations intended by the user.”“One of the defendants was arrested at Los Angeles International Airport over the weekend as he was on his way to a conference. The other five defendants remain in China.”SOURCES: BBC, New York Times, Federal Bureau of Investigationhttp://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-32805227http://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/20/technology/6-chinese-men-indicted-in-theft-of-code-from-us-tech-companies.html?_r=0http://www.fbi.gov/sanfrancisco/press-releases/2015/chine