      <title>More than 33 million birds affected by avian flu in the U.S.</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twThree deadly strains of avian flu, H5N8, H5N2 and the highly pathogenic HPAI strain, have hit North America's poultry flocks, causing the worst avian flu outbreak in the U.S. on record.More than 160 cases of avian flu have been reported since December, affecting more than 33 million turkeys, chickens and ducks who have been killed or are expected to be culled in 15 different states in the U.S., according to the U.S. Department of Agriculture.Wisconsin, Minnesota and Iowa have declared state emergencies due to the epidemic. According to the USDA, about 40 percent of egg-laying hens in Iowa are dead or will be euthanized, and more than 14 percent of hens have died in Minnesota. In Minnesota, lawmakers have approved $20 million funding to help farmers contain the virus. Earlier this year, the federal government approved $330 million in funding to help states fight the spread of bird flu.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. States affected by bird flu2. How the virus is spread3. How to affected birds are culled4. How bird carcasses are disposed ofVOICEOVER (in English): “More than 33 million turkeys, chickens and ducks in 15 different states have been affected by the avian flu since December.”“About 40 percent of hens in Iowa are dead or will be euthanized, while in Minnesota, more than 14 percent of hens have died.”“The virus is spread by wild bird droppings left on farms, dust and dander, or from the shoes of a person who moves from one facility to another.”“The infected birds are culled using carbon dioxide gas or a water-based foam that is similar to that used to suppress a fire.”“The carcasses are then buried in giant rectangular pits or incinerated.”SOURCES: http://in.reuters.com/article/2015/05/12/us-health-birdflu-usa-timeline-idINKBN0NX2QH20150512http://www.latimes.com/science/la-na-bird-flu-20150517-story.htmlhttp://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2015/05/17/state-leaders-approve-funding-to-stop-bird-flu/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
