      <title>U.S. plans on sending Australia B-1 bombers to ensure freedom of navigation in South China Sea</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twThe United States military plans to station B-1 strategic bombers and surveillance aircraft in Australia, according to U.S. Defence Department Assistant Secretary for Asian and Pacific Security Affairs David Shear.The move is seen as part of an effort to deter Chinese ambitions in the South China Sea. Shear’s announcement came ahead of any announcement by the Australian government.The U.S. is already planning to boost naval forces and airpower in the South China Sea to assert the right of free passage, as China continues its efforts to assert its maritime territorial claims in the region. China has already begun construction of airfields and artificial islands in the South China Sea.The B-1 Lancer bomber, commonly called "Bone" (originally from "B-One") was first deployed by the US Air Force in the mid 1980s, according to the Sydney Morning Herald. The aircraft is expected to continue in serve as a strategic bomber until the mid 2030s.The aircraft is able to rapidly deliver 84 500-pound bombs and is currently being used to attack Islamic State in Iraq, ABC News in Australia reported.Shear also said U.S. military movements will also be taking place in other countries in the region, including the “deployment of Global Hawks and F-35s in Japan.” Washington will be adding to the stock of V-22s in Japan, according to Shear.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. China making maritime claims in South China Sea2. China building artificial islands3. U.S. increasing naval forces in the region4. U.S. sends B-1 bomber to Australia5. Aircraft payload6. U.S. sends Global Hawks, F-35s and V-22s to JapanVOICEOVER (in English): “As China continues to boost its maritime territorial claims in the South China Sea through the construction of airfields and artificial islands,”“The U.S. is increasing its naval forces and airpower in the region to assert the right of free passage.”“The U.S. military has announced plans to station B-1 strategic bombers and surveillance aircraft in Australia.”“The B-1 Lancer bomber is able to quickly deliver a total of 84 500-pound bombs ‘anywhere in the world, at any time’. It is currently being used against the Islamic State in Iraq.”“The U.S. defence secretary stated that Global Hawks and F-35s would also be deployed to Japan, while the military would add to the stock of V-22 Ospreys in the country.”SOURCES: Sydney Morning Herald, Australia Broadcasting Corporation, RThttp://www.smh.com.au/world/b1-bombers-coming-to-australia-to-deter-beijings-south-china-sea-ambitions-us-20150514-gh23zl.htmlhttp://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-05-15/united-states-sends-b1-bomber-aircraft-to-australia/6471528http://rt.com/usa/258713-b1-bombers-china-dispute/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
