      <title>How a hung parliament in the UK works</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twAs millions of voters head to the polls in the UK general elections, the country could be heading toward a hung parliament.In UK elections, a party must win at least 326 of 650 seats in the House of Commons to obtain an absolute majority.In the event that no party wins that number, a hung parliament occurs,, which means that no party has the majority.Without the cooperation of other parties, the party with the plurality of seats might not have enough votes to pass legislation.In this event, the largest parties -- either the Conservative Party or the Labour Party -- can attempt to form a coalition with other parties and reach a majority.If there is no ground for a coalition, the party with most seats will have to start negotiations with the other parties.The final results of the UK general elections are expected on May 8th in the afternoon.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. House of Commons: conservative party getting 326 seats (representational)2. Hung parliament: no party has more than 325 seats3. A party with less than 326 seats might not get legislation passed4. Leading party creating a coalition with other parties5. Leading party negotiating with other parties VOICEOVER (in English): “In UK elections, an absolute majority happens when a party has won at least 326 out of 650 seats in the House of Commons.”“In the event that no party gets that number, a hung parliament is formed, which means that no party has the majority of seats available.”“Without the cooperation of other parties, the party with the plurality of seats might not have enough votes to pass legislation.”“In this event, the largest parties -- either the Conservative Party or the Labour Party -- can attempt to form a coalition with other parties and reach a majority.”“If there is no ground for a coalition, the party with more seats will have to start negotiations with the other parties.”SOURCES: THE GUARDIAN , BBChttp://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/06/general-election-2015-britain-heading-for-hung-parliamenthttp://www.bbc.com/news/election-2015-32618577***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
