      <title>New England Patriots probably deflated footballs: report</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twA 243-page report released by the NFL on Wednesday has revealed “it is more probable, than not” that New England Patriots personnel deliberately deflated footballs below league standards, according to a New York Times report. The long awaited report, commissioned in response to the“deflategate” controversy, investigated allegations that New England Patriots personnel purposely deflated balls used in January’s AFC championship game, which saw them defeat the Indianapolis Colts 45-7.The report says New England Patriots locker room attendant Jim McNally and equipment assistant John Jastremski released air from 11 of 12 game balls with Patriots quarterback Tom Brady aware of the deflation.  No other Patriots personnel, including Coach Bill Belichick, are believed to have been aware of the deflated footballs. A regulation NFL football has to be inflated between 12.5 to 13.5 pounds per inch. 11 footballs tested during the AFC championship game in January, were found to be significantly underinflated.Deflated balls are easier to throw, catch, and grip than standard regulation footballs. The report separately determined that the Patriots had not deliberately tried to introduce an improper football for kicking and cleared kicker Stephen Gostkowski of any wrongdoing.RUNDOWN SHOWS:Standard football vs deflated Patriots football Two Patriots assistants deflating 11 footballs Tom Brady knows about the deflating footballs Standard football vs deflated football thrown farther because of weightStephen Gostkowski successfully kicks the football in the goalOfficials find out 11 footballs have been deflated VOICEOVER (in English): "A regulation NFL football has to be inflated between 12.5 to 13.5 pounds per inch. 11 footballs tested during the AFC championship game in January, were found to be significantly underinflated.""A New England Patriots locker room attendant and equipment assistant are believed to have released air from 11 of 12 game balls with Patriots quarterback Tom Brady aware of the deflation." "Deflated balls are easier to throw, catch, and grip than standard regulation footballs. The report separately determined that the Patriots had not deliberately" "tried to introduce an improper football for kicking and cleared kicker Stephen Gostkowski of any wrongdoing.""A member of the Indianapolis Colts, whom the Patriots defeated 45-7, gave officials a ball that was underinflated during halftime." SOURCES: New York Timeswww.nytimes.com/2015/05/07/sports/patriots-probably-deflated-footballs-on-purpose-report-says.html?hp&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&module=first-column-region&region=top-news&WT.nav=top-news***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
