      <title>Daredevil Nik Wallenda walks across ferris wheel</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twDaredevil Nik Wallenda added a new record to his thick portfolio Wednesday morning when he successfully walked across a giant moving ferris wheel in Orlando.  The Orlando Eye rotated at walking pace as Nik crossed from one pod to another, moving against the spin’s direction. The new ferris wheel is 400 feet tall, which is roughly equivalent to a 35-story building and taller than the Statue of Liberty. It’s not Nik’s highest accomplishment -- he was about 1400 feet in the air when he crossed the Grand Canyon -- but normally he has a balancing pole with him, which aids his center of gravity. “Without a balancing pole, it’s really challenging,” Wallenda said in a video interview provided by Reuters. “Everything happens quicker. With the balancing pole, it buys me a little time,” he said. He also had to duck under obstacles during the ferris wheel walk, which added an additional challenge. “There’s gonna be a lot going on for sure,” Wallenda said prior to the walk. Overnight rain made the steel beam slippery, and Wallenda estimated the wind to be at 20 mph as he crossed the wheel. Despite the challenges, Wallenda completed the walk in just four minutes. The walk aired live on NBC’s “Today.” The Orlando Eye is the tallest observation wheel on the East Coast, USA Today reported. The ferris wheel is set to open publically on May 4th. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1.Highlight shows pathway across ferris wheel rim 2.35-story building next to ferris wheel to demonstrate height3.Comparison of ferris wheel to Grand Canyon tightrope walk4.Nik Wallenda using a balancing pole to cross a tightrope5.Nik Wallenda crossing the ferris wheel without a balancing bar6.Water dripping from steel beams, wind blowing as Nik crossesVOICEOVER (in English): "The Orlando Eye rotated at walking pace as Nik crossed from one pod to another Wednesday morning." "The new ferris wheel is 400 feet tall -- about the equivalent of a 35-story building." " It’s not Nik’s highest accomplishment. He was about 1400 feet in the air when he crossed the Grand Canyon." "But normally he has a balancing pole with him, which aids his center of gravity. During Wednesday’s walk he had no balancing pole, AND he had to duck under obstacles." "The walk was further complicated by the overnight rain in Orlando and 20-mile-per-hour wind." SOURCES: Reuters, Today, USA Today, The Orlando Eye, WRALhttp://www.reuters.com/article/2015/04/29/us-usa-florida-wallenda-idUSKBN0NJ2E420150429http://www.today.com/news/nik-wallenda-prepares-walk-spinning-orlando-eye-live-today-show-t18086http://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/destinations/2015/04/29/nik-wallenda-orlando-eye/26523155/https://www.officialorlandoeye.com/http://www.wral.com/nik-wallenda-completes-walk-of-400-foot-wheel-in-orlando/14612381/***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
