      <title>Florida avocado crop threatened by deadly fungus (UPDATE)</title>
      <description><![CDATA[CORRECTION: Refeed replaces SD video with HD videoRESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twResearchers in Florida are using dogs and drones in the fight against a disease that is threatening the state’s multimillion dollar avocado industry, as part of a Florida International University program funded by the Florida Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services.The disease, laurel wilt, is caused by the fungus Raffaelea lauricola, and kills more than 90 percent of trees within six weeks of infection. Laurel wilt is vectored by the ambrosia beetle, an invasive species from Asia.For the project, researchers are testing the use of a drone and dogs to detect the disease before symptoms are visible to the human eye. Using drones allows large areas to be scanned much faster than it would take humans to examine every individual tree.The drone uses a digital thermal imaging camera to scan areas for infected trees. If a problem area is detected, disease-sniffing dogs are dispatched to confirm the presence of an infection. If the infection is caught early enough, the tree can be saved by treating it with fungicide.Florida’s avocado industry is worth more than $35 million a year to the state’s economy.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. A fungus-carrying ambrosia beetle bores into a tree2. The beetle feeds on fungus growing inside the tree, and the infected tree wilts3. A drone flies over an avocado orchard and detects an infection with its thermal imaging camera4. Dogs inspect the infected tree5. The infected tree is cut down and burned6. Nearby trees are treated with fungicideVOICEOVER (in English): “Laurel wilt is vectored by the ambrosia beetle, an invasive species from Asia. The fungus is introduced when the beetle bores into a tree.”“The fungus grows inside the tree and the beetle feeds on it. The fungus spreads in the tree’s vascular system, causing it to wilt and die.”"Researchers in Florida are using a drone with a thermal digital imaging camera to detect infections that are not yet visible to the human eye. If a problem area is spotted, disease-sniffing dogs are used to confirm the infection.""If detected early enough, the tree can be saved with fungicide. If not, the tree is cut down and burned.""The surrounding trees are then treated with fungicide to contain the outbreak."SOURCES: WSNV, Georgia Forestry Commission, Florida International University, University of Floridahttp://www.wsvn.com/story/28834461/fiu-researchers-use-dogs-drones-to-search-for-diseased-beetleshttp://www.gatrees.org/forest-management/forest-health/laurel-wilt-disease/http://news.fiu.edu/2015/03/canines-battle-deadly-avocado-fungus/86155http://edis.ifas.ufl.edu/fe837***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
