      <title>Embryonic twin thought to be a tumor removed from woman&#x2019;s brain</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twLos Angeles doctors discovered and removed an embryonic twin from inside the brain of a 26-year-old Indiana university student who doctors earlier had thought was suffering from a brain tumor.The embryo inside Yamini Karanam’s brain, despite having never developed, was found with bones, hair and teeth, Sky News reported.Karanam first sought medical help last year after she experienced comprehension problems. Doctors told her she was affected by a brain tumor. Instead, after surgery she found out that the tumor was in fact an embryonic twin. An embryonic twin occurs when a twin embryo develops in utero and the pair doesn’t fully separate. One embryo then keeps developing at the expense of the other one.The non-dominant embryo eventually dies in utero and is partially or completely reabsorbed by the dominant twin.Karanam made fun of her embryonic twin by telling NBC Los Angeles that it was her “evil twin sister who’s been torturing me for the past 26 years.”After undergoing minimally invasive brain surgery, she is expected to make full recovery.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Embryonic twin bone, hair and teeth2. Twin embryo developing inside a uterus3. Two embryos not fully separating 4. One of the embryos dominating the other5. The non dominant embryo dying and being absorbed by the dominant embryoVOICEOVER (in English): “The embryo inside the woman’s brain, despite never developing, was still found with bones, hair and teeth.”“Los Angeles doctors discovered and removed an embryonic twin with its own bones, hair, and teeth inside the brain of a 26-year-old Indiana university student.”“An embryonic twin occurs when a twin embryo develops inside the uterus and the pair doesn’t fully separate. “One embryo then keeps developing at the expense of the other.”“The non-dominant embryo eventually dies in utero and is partially or completely reabsorbed by the dominant twin.” SOURCES: NBC Los Angeles, Sky Newshttp://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Embryonic-Twin-Discovered-in-Womans-Brain-During-Surgery-300891281.htmlhttp://news.sky.com/story/1470409/evil-twin-embryo-removed-from-womans-brain***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
