      <title>Britain's garrison on the Falkland Islands</title>
      <description><![CDATA[Britain said on Thursday it had summoned Argentina’s ambassador to explain a threat to take legal action against British energy companies drilling for oil in the Falklands, just days after the 33rd anniversary of the Falklands Conflict.The threat comes a week after Argentine President Cristina Fernandez de Kirchner and ambassador Alicia Castro criticized Britain’s plan to beef up defences on the islands amid reports of an increased risk of invasion from Argentina.Some British 1,200 troops are based at the British garrison on the Falklands at Mount Pleasant, about 35 miles from the capital, Stanley.Last month, Britain announced it would send two Chinook helicopters to the islands as well as a new air defense missile system, as part of a £180 million upgrade to the islands’ defenses. The announcement was made amid reports that Argentina was in talks to lease 12 Sukhoi Su-24 bombers from Russia.Argentina has intensified its claims to the islands in recent years. Britain and Argentina fought a brief war over the islands in 1982 after Argentina invaded the islands. More than 600 Argentine and 225 British servicemen were killed in the conflict.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Location of Mount Pleasant, Stanley and Mare Harbour on the Falklands2. British ground forces in the Falklands3. British air units in the Falklands4. British naval units operating in or near the Falklands5. Planned upgrades to Falklands garrisonVOICEOVER (in English): “The British garrison on the Falklands is based at Mount Pleasant, about 35 miles from the capital, Stanley. A port facility is maintained at Mare Harbour for Royal Navy ships.”“1,200 troops are based at Mount Pleasant. These include an infantry company, engineer squadron, signals unit and logistics group, as well as a Rapier air defense system.”“Air units protecting the Falklands include four Eurofighter Typhoon jets, one KC2 Voyager air tanker and one C3 Hercules transport aircraft, and two Sea King helicopters.”“Royal Navy ships patrolling the islands include a River Class patrol vessel, and a frigate or guided missile cruiser. A nuclear submarine may also be deployed to the area.”“Last month, Britain announced it would send two Chinook helicopters to the islands as well as a new missile system to replace the Rapier, amid reports that Argentina was in talks to lease 12 Sukhoi Su-24 bombers from Russia.”SOURCES: British Parliament, Sky News, Reuters, Royal Navy, Defense News, Flight Global, The Independent, Express, Newseek, Economistwww.parliament.uk/briefing-papers/SN06201.pdfhttp://news.sky.com/story/1461609/ambassador-summoned-over-falklands-oil-threathttp://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCAKBN0N019R20150409http://www.defensenews.com/story/defense/air-space/strike/2014/12/30/russia-argentina-jets-food/21045405/http://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/clydehttp://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/argentina-seeks-kfir-deal-with-israel-394770/http://www.defensenews.com/story/defense/international/americas/2014/11/30/argentinas-jet-fighter-replacement-options-narrow/19698473/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/argentines-falklands-minister-there-is-absolutely-no-chance-of-another-invasion-9821944.htmlhttp://www.defensenews.com/story/defense/international/americas/2015/01/11/uk-falklands-leapp-air-defense-argentinia/21497721/http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/568489/Argentina-Falklands-Invasion-Handbook-MoD-blunderhttp://www.newsweek.com/argentina-appeals-un-against-british-militarisation-falkland-islands-318348http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/southamerica/falklandislands/11491580/Britains-military-defences-in-the-Falkland-Islands.htmlhttp://www.economist.com/blogs/americasview/2014/02/oil-and-gas-falklands***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
