      <title>UK scientists use medieval remedy to kill superbug MRSA</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twUK Scientists successfully recreated and used a thousand-year-old Anglo Saxon remedy to kill hospital superbug MRSA.Methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus, otherwise known as the superbug MRSA, is a bacteria resistant to many antibiotics. It can cause skin infections and more severe problems such as bloodstream infections and pneumonia in patients in hospitals or nursing homes, according to Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.Scientist from the University of Nottingham used a thousand-year-old remedy for eye infections to tackle MRSA. The remedy included garlic, leek, English wine, cow bile and ‘brass vessels’, which scientists replaced with brass sheets as they are easier to sterilise, according to New Scientist. The potion self-sterilised and killed all the bacteria brought by the leek and garlic soil after nine days of stewing. It was then tested on scraps of mice skin infected with MRSA. The result shows it killed 90 per cent of the bacteria, New Scientist reported.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Illustration of MRSA and its resistance to many antibiotics2. MRSA causes skin and bloodstream infections and pneumonia3. Content of the remedy4. The portion self-sterilised after nine days5. The portion kills 90 percent of MRSA bacteriaVOICEOVER (in English): “Methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus, otherwise known as superbug MRSA, is a bacteria that is resistant to many antibiotics.”“MRSA can cause skin infections and more severe problems such as bloodstream infections and pneumonia in hospital or nursing home patients.” “Scientist from the University of Nottingham recently used a thousand-year-old remedy for eye infections to tackle MRSA. The remedy included garlic, leek, English wine, cow bile while ‘brass vessels’ were replaced with brass sheets as they were easier to sterilise.”“The potion self-sterilised and killed all the bacteria contained in the leek and garlic soil after nine days.”“It was then tested on scraps of mice skin infected with MRSA. The results showed it killed 90 per cent of the bacteria.”SOURCES: New Scientist, BBC, The Independent, CDChttp://www.newscientist.com/article/dn27263-anglo-saxon-remedy-kills-hospital-superbug-mrsa.html#.VRo8LeE0h8Fhttp://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-nottinghamshire-32117815http://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/revolting-recipe-from-the-dark-ages-may-be-key-to-defeat-mrsa-10144616.htmlhttp://www.cdc.gov/mrsa/community/index.html***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
