      <title>Boeing granted patent for force field technology</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twDeflector shields seen in sci-fi movies such as Star Wars may soon be a reality as Boeing has been granted a patent for a shockwave attenuation system which uses an energy shield to protect objects from explosion shockwaves and shrapnel.The system generates a plasma shield using lasers, electricity and microwaves after detecting a nearby explosion. The system is designed to protect objects from the considerable damage that shockwaves and shrapnel can cause following an explosion.A small area is ionized, making the temperature, density and composition inside it different from its surroundings. The shockwaves are either then absorbed, reflected or deflected by the protective arc. The innovative technology has one shortcoming. Since the shield also absorbs light, everyone protected by the system would be completely blind when the system operates.The Defence Science and Technology Laboratory has also been working on a similar defense system.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Shockwaves and shrapnel damaging a US hummer 2. Shockwave attenuation system creating a plasma field 3. Small region ionized 4. Reflected, deflected and absorbed shockwaves 5. Light reflected by shockwave attenuation system VOICEOVER (in English): “Following an explosion, shockwaves and shrapnel can cause considerable damage.” “Boeing has obtained a patent for a shockwave attenuation system. The system generates a plasma shield using lasers, electricity and microwaves after detecting a nearby explosion.” “A small area is ionized, making the temperature, density and composition inside differ from its surroundings.” “The shockwaves are either then absorbed, reflected or deflected by the protective arc.” “The innovative technology has one shortcoming. Since the shield also absorbs light, everyone protected by the system will be completely blind when the system is in operation.” SOURCES: CNET, Express http://www.cnet.com/news/boeing-patents-star-wars-style-force-fields/http://www.express.co.uk/life-style/science-technology/565768/US-Patent-Boeing-Star-Wars-Force-Field-Technology***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
