      <title>New York City&#x2019;s Second Avenue subway line construction may be delayed again</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twA $15 billion gap in the New York City Metropolitan Transportation Authority’s five-year capital plan may curtail the city’s Second Avenue subway project. According to MTA Chairman Tom Prendergast, funding gaps in MTA’s $32 billion capital proposal will probably mean that the second phase of the construction project will be eliminated. This phase of the construction project extends from 96th Street to 125th Street in East Harlem. Prendergast told the New York Daily News that the MTA’s priorities are repairing and replacing equipment in the existing subway lines rather than extending new lines. If the Second Avenue subway project is completed, the new subway line will stretch 8.5 miles along the east side of Manhattan and connect East Harlem to the island’s southern tip. The project’s first phase, which extends from 96th Street to 63rd Street, will be completed by the end of 2016. As a project that’s been in the works since the 1920, the Second Avenue subway line has endured numerous false starts and delays mainly due to lack of funding. The New York State budget is up for negotiation this April though, and Governor Cuomo has hinted that transit funding is up for negotiation later this year. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Location of subway construction site on the Upper East Side2. Four different phases of the subway project3. Length of new subway route4. Elevators and escalators eliminated from subway stationsVOICEOVER (in English): TITLE CUT [PHOTO SOURCE:  METROPOLITAN TRANSPORTATION AUTHORITYFUNDING CRISIS CUTS SHORTNEW YORK CITY SUBWAY ROUTEread this VO for title cut:“New York City Metropolitan Transportation Authority’s funding gap may cut short the city’s Second Avenue subway line.”[PHOTO: METROPOLITAN TRANSPORTATION AUTHORITY 2]“New York City’s Second Avenue subway project was first proposed in the 1920s. Progress has been slow though, and after almost a century, planned sections of the network are far from becoming a reality.”[CUT 1]“Construction on New York City’s Second Avenue subway line began on the Upper East Side in 2007.”[CUT 2]“The first phase of the construction runs from 96th Street on Manhattan’s Upper East Side, and runs to 63rd Street. This phase will be completed by December 2016.” “The second phase stretches from 96th street to 125th Street in East Harlem, the third phase from 63rd Street to Houston Street, and the last extends from Houston Street to Hanover Square.” [CUT 3]“When it’s fully completed, the Second Avenue subway line will be 8.5 miles long, more than half of the length of Manhattan.”“However, because the Metropolitan Transportation Authority is $15 billion dollars short in their five-year capital plan, phase two of the construction may be eliminated.”“Other potential cuts include elevators and escalators in some of the new stations.”SOURCES: New York Daily News, Metropolitan Transportation Authority, Fox 5, Gothamisthttp://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/mta-chief-ave-subway-line-stopped-short-article-1.2134591http://web.mta.info/capital/sas_alt.htmlhttp://www.myfoxny.com/story/28252912/second-avenue-subway-line-delayed-againhttp://gothamist.com/2015/03/03/mta_2nd_ave_subway.php***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
