      <title>Nineteen manatees rescued from drainage pipe in Florida</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twNineteen manatees were rescued early Tuesday morning from a storm drain at Satellite Beach, Florida. The manatees, also known as sea cows, were apparently trying to find their way to warmer waters when they became lodged in the drainage pipe, officials and local media said.Reuters reports the rescue started mid-afternoon on Monday when Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission biologist, Ann Spellman, sounded the alarm, according to Florida Today.Spellman told Florida Today that she had a hunch, which led city workers to check the 100-150-feet-long drain pipe.Although experts were able to coax some manatees to swim out of the pipe, video footage of the event shows the pipe also being cut and water being vacuumed from the area before manatees were hoisted out with heavy machinery and carried to a nearby canal in slings.Manatees, also known as sea cows, often leave the Indian River Lagoon during cold snaps for warmer waters in the canals. The ones that became stuck in the pipe probably followed ended up there by following each other, Reuters reports Spellman as saying.The rescue, which included local police working alongside experts from SeaWorld, was completed at about 2:00 a.m. local time (0100 ET), Satellite Beach Fire Department Captain Jay Dragon said.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Manatees entering drain pipe2. Length of drain pipe, pipe cut open3. Water vacuumed out4. Manatee hoisted out with heavy machinery5. Manatee carried to canal6. Manatee released into the waterVOICEOVER (in English): “Nineteen manatees became lodged in a drainage pipe at Satellite Beach in Florida on Monday.”“The 100-150-foot-long drain pipe had to be cut open during the hours-long rescue.”“Water was vacuumed from the area as manatees were moved onto slings and hoisted out with heavy machinery.”“They were then carried in the slings to a nearby canal, where they were released back into the water.”SOURCES: Reuters, CNNhttp://www.reuters.com/article/2015/02/24/us-usa-manatees-florida-idUSKBN0LS08U20150224http://www.cnn.com/videos/us/2015/02/25/erin-pkg-moos-manatees-rescued-from-drainpipe.cnn***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
