      <title>Ecuador declares emergency over Galapagos grounded ship</title>
      <description><![CDATA[RESTRICTIONS: NONE For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twThe Ecuadorean government has declared a state of emergency in the Galapagos Islands a week after a ship carrying hazardous materials ran aground.The freighter Floreana was carrying supplies from the island of San Cristobal to Santa Cruz when it ran aground near Puerto Baquerizo Moreno.The ship was carrying 1,400 tons of cargo, including 48 tons of asphalt emulsion, more than 100 gas cylinders as well as 10,000 gallons of fuel oil.The small amounts of diesel and hydraulic oil that have leaked from the ship so far have been contained by booms.A salvage operation is expected to begin soon amid fears that the boat and it’s cargo pose a risk to the fragile ecosystem of the Galapagos National Park and its unique wildlife.The Floreana was the only ship that carried supplies to the islands’ 30,000 inhabitants.The Ecuadorian Air Force will airlift supplies to the islanders until a replacement ship is purchased, the provincial council announced. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Location of Galapagos Islands and shipwreck2. Intended route of freighter Floreana and location of grounding3. Details of ship’s cargo4. Depiction of booms preventing oil spill5. Detail of Galapagos unique wildlifeVOICEOVER (in English): “The Ecuadorean government has declared a state of emergency in the Galapagos Islands a week after a ship carrying hazardous materials ran aground.”“The freighter Floreana was carrying supplies from the island of San Cristobal to Santa Cruz when it ran aground near Puerto Baquerizo Moreno." “The ship was carrying 1,400 tons of cargo, including 48 tons of asphalt emulsion, more than 100 gas cylinders as well as 10,000 gallons of fuel oil.”The small amounts of diesel and hydraulic oil that have leaked from the ship so far have been contained by booms..”A salvage operation is expected to begin soon amid fears that the boat and it’s cargo pose a risk to the fragile ecosystem of the Galapagos National Park and its unique wildlife.”SOURCES: Huffington Post, Ecuavisahttp://www.huffingtonpost.com/cecilia-alvear/in-galapagos-another-frei_b_6598890.htmlhttp://www.ecuavisa.com/articulo/noticias/nacional/97279-barco-carga-floreana-encallo-isla-san-cristobal***For story suggestions please contact tips@nma.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
